INSERT INTO `grammar` (`id`, `created_at`, `status`, `updated_at`, `description`, `image`, `title`, `views`, `definition`, `example`, `file`, `questions`, `route_node_id`) VALUES (1,'2025-05-17 09:36:42.256595',_binary '','2025-06-03 17:47:53.319404','This lesson introduces the Simple Present Tense, one of the most basic and commonly used tenses in English. You will learn how to form it, when to use it, and how to apply it correctly in both affirmative and negative forms.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/1-0d2af5f1-d58e-40c6-848d-44e806c3dbf2','Simple Present Tense',2,'The Simple Present Tense is used to describe: Habits and routines, General truths and facts, Scheduled events (especially timetables), Feelings, thoughts, and states','I go to school every day.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/1-7eb847da-1d9b-400b-92da-de4072e975c2','7,8,9,10,11',NULL),(2,'2025-06-01 18:29:50.606433',_binary '','2025-06-11 23:06:45.572624','Learn how to use the Present Simple tense to talk about habits, general truths, and repeated actions.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/2-86154543-e90f-4bc6-8aa5-8b990e98777d','Present Simple Tense',4,'The Present Simple tense is used to describe habitual actions, general facts, and permanent situations.','She drinks coffee every morning.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/2-9f7b6ded-bdfb-4f75-ac0e-26ffae791ccb','30,31,32,33,34',NULL),(3,'2025-06-01 18:38:38.122511',_binary '','2025-06-11 23:46:55.013682','Learn how to use the Present Continuous Tense to talk about actions happening now or around the current time.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/3-d33c6a3e-0c77-4dc5-8e28-64fa4c80e6f0','Present Continuous Tense',1,'The Present Continuous Tense is used to describe actions that are happening right now or around the current time (but not necessarily at the exact moment of speaking).','She is reading a book right now.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/3-974fe689-fa0e-4ec3-bf6d-eec980d66b87','35,36,37,38,39',NULL),(4,'2025-06-01 18:47:24.397247',_binary '','2025-06-03 15:59:13.476128','Learn how to use the Simple Future Tense to talk about actions that will happen later.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/4-fc9cadd7-03e3-410e-9185-ff3c99eca7f4','Simple Future Tense',0,'The Simple Future Tense is used to describe actions that will happen later, often for predictions, promises, or spontaneous decisions. It is formed with \"will + base verb\" or \"be going to + base verb.\"','She will travel to Paris next month.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/4-f64a47b8-9223-444f-a76a-1747e59ee033','40,41,42,43,44',NULL),(5,'2025-06-01 18:53:55.458931',_binary '','2025-06-03 16:56:48.554138','Learn how to use the Simple Past Tense to talk about completed actions in the past.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/5-2ca5f6c0-02de-456e-a487-5a139c6453f2','Simple Past Tense',0,'The Simple Past Tense is used to describe actions that started and finished at a specific time in the past. Regular verbs form the past tense by adding \"-ed\", while irregular verbs have unique past forms.','She visited her grandparents last weekend.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/5-ca859fe7-4113-46ad-bdf2-9cf4a954026e','45,46,47,48,49',NULL),(6,'2025-06-01 19:23:55.810353',_binary '','2025-06-03 17:04:04.451561','Learn how to use the Present Perfect Tense to talk about past actions connected to the present.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-7fd7d5e5-f282-44a8-9e67-caeba7e0ea14','Present Perfect Tense',0,'The Present Perfect Tense connects past actions to the present moment. It describes:Experiences in one\'s life, recently completed actions, actions that began in the past and continue now','I have visited Paris three times.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/6-b814bec3-4f13-48b6-9491-855bc97edf90','50,51,52,53,54',NULL),(7,'2025-06-11 15:52:16.151947',_binary '','2025-06-11 15:54:50.333920','This lesson teaches students how to use the past perfect tense to describe actions that were completed before other past events. Students will learn to sequence past events correctly and understand the relationship between different past actions.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-edb2c955-12a6-421b-a1e6-cc883c8a1941','Mastering the Past Perfect: Actions Before Actions',0,'The past perfect tense is used to describe an action that was completed before another action or time in the past. It shows which action happened first when we talk about two past events.','When I arrived at the cinema, the movie had already started.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-1466a979-8b8c-4960-842e-579a9f4bb1ae','107,108,109,110,111',NULL),(8,'2025-06-11 15:58:37.714399',_binary '','2025-06-11 16:01:03.189793','This lesson teaches students how to use the future perfect tense to describe actions that will be completed before a specific time in the future. Students will learn to express completed future actions and make predictions about future accomplishments.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-ebbdc30d-a66b-4df1-b3ec-f9a6bb48a607','Looking Ahead: Future Perfect Tense Mastery',0,'The future perfect tense describes an action that will be completed before a specific time or event in the future. It shows what will have happened by a certain point.','By 2030, I will have graduated from university.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-5afdfac0-8e7c-49e4-9503-0db5d84ebe29','112,113',NULL),(9,'2025-06-11 16:06:19.523270',_binary '','2025-06-11 16:09:09.855639','This lesson teaches students how to use the future continuous tense to describe actions that will be happening at a specific time in the future. Students will learn to express ongoing future activities and temporary situations.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-4f4f3982-1005-41fa-9d16-e94d6e5e986e','In Progress Tomorrow: Future Continuous Tense',0,'The future continuous tense describes an action that will be in progress at a specific time in the future. It shows what will be happening at a particular moment.','At 8 PM tomorrow, I will be watching a movie.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-83964521-47dd-4fbd-b243-8a525a8c05da','114,115,116,117',NULL),(10,'2025-06-11 16:10:37.998732',_binary '','2025-06-11 16:13:29.774098','This lesson teaches students how to use the past continuous tense to describe actions that were in progress at a specific time in the past. Students will learn to express ongoing past activities and interrupted actions.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-c1cc2fda-27d1-43bd-9f8f-3d93c3a3b358','What Was Happening: Past Continuous Tense',0,'The past continuous tense describes an action that was in progress at a specific time in the past or when another action interrupted it. It shows what was happening at a particular moment.','I was reading a book when the phone rang.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-9ba3ac58-f96b-4993-a36d-58ac068dc06d','118',NULL),(11,'2025-06-11 16:15:31.787325',_binary '','2025-06-11 16:17:48.169310','This lesson teaches students how to use conditional sentences (if clauses) to express possibilities, hypothetical situations, and consequences. Students will learn the different types of conditionals and their proper structures.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-dc6a74c8-9cc1-4f2a-9249-ff636a740ff0','If Statements: Mastering Conditional Sentences',0,'Conditional sentences express what happens or would happen under certain conditions. They consist of two parts: the \"if clause\" (condition) and the \"main clause\" (result). There are four main types: Zero, First, Second, and Third conditionals.','If it rains tomorrow, I will stay at home.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-56945230-2d81-45e9-8f83-8b4eef4d6cc9','119',NULL),(12,'2025-06-11 16:19:29.436665',_binary '','2025-06-11 16:20:00.572169','From Active to Passive: Mastering the Passive Voice','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-b5d551dd-05a3-4536-9392-932d4aab478d','From Active to Passive: Mastering the Passive Voice',0,'The passive voice emphasizes the action or the person/thing receiving the action rather than who performs it. The subject receives the action instead of performing it. The structure is: be + past participle.','The lesson is explained by the teacher.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-ad0d3ad3-5400-41b1-aea1-9110ca4e181e','120',NULL),(13,'2025-06-11 16:23:22.508536',_binary '','2025-06-11 16:24:36.777787','This lesson teaches students how to use relative clauses to provide additional information about nouns and connect ideas smoothly. Students will learn to use relative pronouns and create more complex, natural-sounding sentences.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-8bee30b6-777c-4de8-bbd7-bb8c131308ea','Connecting Ideas: Mastering Relative Clauses',0,'Relative clauses give extra information about a noun in the main sentence. They begin with relative pronouns (who, which, that, whose, where, when) and help combine sentences to avoid repetition. There are defining and non-defining relative clauses.','I met a woman who speaks five languages.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-f490b79a-41ca-4515-94b7-1bfc60f7c847','121',NULL),(14,'2025-06-13 20:01:30.047679',_binary '','2025-06-13 20:02:07.869016','Students will learn to express real and hypothetical situations using appropriate conditional structures.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-738015bb-0758-4603-a8d8-11e84f29988a','English Grammar Lesson: Conditional Sentences',0,'Conditional sentences express situations that depend on certain conditions, typically consisting of an \"if\" clause (condition) and a main clause (result).','If it rains tomorrow, I will stay at home.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-4a21670d-63c2-49fd-8935-e5fc21606ac9','145',NULL),(15,'2025-06-13 20:04:57.821770',_binary '','2025-06-13 20:10:00.528132','Students will learn to transform active sentences into passive form and understand when passive voice is appropriate.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-a338297c-cf99-48f2-a33a-28bab4583e83','English Grammar Lesson: Passive Voice',0,'Passive voice is formed with \"be + past participle\" and shifts focus from the subject performing the action to the object receiving the action.','The report was written by the manager.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-5e397669-4165-4669-8e3f-aa5c38c0cfe0','146',NULL),(16,'2025-06-13 20:23:48.046928',_binary '','2025-06-13 20:24:32.038660','This lesson focuses on transforming direct speech into reported speech, including necessary changes in tenses, pronouns, and time expressions.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-67bbed6c-282a-45bf-a94b-142823c2b713','Reported Speech (Indirect Speech)',0,'Reported speech is used to tell someone what another person said without using their exact words, typically introduced by reporting verbs like \"said,\" \"told,\" or \"asked.\"','\"I am studying English,\" she said. → Reported: She said that she was studying English.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-1c32c302-01ae-4cbc-ad03-40d814fc56bc','147',NULL),(17,'2025-06-14 15:41:53.323001',_binary '','2025-06-14 15:42:37.140525','Students will learn to identify when each article is appropriate in different contexts.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-4d7d728a-b485-4bba-b891-20e9da062d1a','English Grammar Lesson: Articles',0,'Articles are words that define nouns as specific or unspecific, including \"the\" (definite article), \"a/an\" (indefinite articles), and zero article (no article used).','I saw a cat in the garden. The cat was sleeping under an old tree.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-f27c48f6-6c7f-44e7-99b3-ebf19c36bbce','148',NULL),(18,'2025-06-14 15:44:56.436909',_binary '','2025-06-14 15:45:29.394478','Students will learn common patterns and exceptions in English grammar.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-beff9d1e-4f48-4173-a0cb-7e2c498d0bd9','English Grammar Lesson: Gerunds and Infinitives',0,'Gerunds are verbs ending in -ing that function as nouns, while infinitives are \"to + base verb\" forms that can function as nouns, adjectives, or adverbs.','I enjoy swimming, but I decided to learn tennis instead.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-42254682-47e0-468c-bb5f-28990a375117','149',NULL),(19,'2025-06-14 15:47:37.132238',_binary '','2025-06-14 15:48:55.578540','Students will learn to combine sentences and provide additional information about nouns.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-411b4f34-afd6-4220-b436-2b7374f1d7cc','English Grammar Lesson: Relative Clauses',0,'Relative clauses are dependent clauses that modify nouns or pronouns, introduced by relative pronouns and providing essential or additional information about the antecedent.','The book that I bought yesterday is very interesting.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-50ad3df7-9fc2-4792-88eb-1485a64f8203','150',NULL),(20,'2025-06-14 15:50:43.709722',_binary '','2025-06-14 15:51:21.562684','Students will learn to make effective comparisons using different grammatical patterns.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-853cd769-1124-44f2-9c25-94d0ab4565a3','Comparisons',0,'Comparisons express differences or similarities between two or more items using comparative forms (comparing two things) and superlative forms (comparing three or more things).','This book is more interesting than that one, but it\'s not as expensive as the hardcover edition.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-aaa5bfd3-e803-47d7-98f2-9123f5c043a8','151',NULL),(21,'2025-06-14 15:53:08.332503',_binary '','2025-06-14 15:54:10.365017','Students will learn to distinguish between different modals and use them appropriately in various contexts.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-340cb61b-d7cb-44a8-9560-6594a91150de','Modal Verbs',0,'Modal verbs are auxiliary verbs that express necessity, possibility, permission, or ability, and are followed by the base form of the main verb without \"to.\"','You should study harder, and you must submit your assignment by Friday.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-a0c00dc6-6233-48ea-8fd9-6fdb33b642df','152',NULL),(22,'2025-06-14 15:56:45.996925',_binary '','2025-06-14 15:57:23.791650','Students will learn to distinguish between subjunctive and indicative mood.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-cdee540d-d2e5-40e8-b8b1-7f520eb54d15','English Grammar Lesson: Subjunctive Mood',0,'The subjunctive mood expresses hypothetical situations, wishes, demands, or suggestions, often using special verb forms that differ from normal indicative mood patterns.','I suggest that he study harder for the exam.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-2ea5600d-8e12-440c-9c5d-c8cd71bfbe6e','153',NULL),(23,'2025-06-14 15:59:40.592003',_binary '','2025-06-14 16:00:20.599773','Students will learn to create balanced and rhythmic sentences.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-46efd38f-b2a0-402a-9b7b-e388cf2a923d','Parallel Structure',0,'Parallel structure means using the same grammatical form for words, phrases, or clauses that have the same function in a sentence, creating balance and clarity in writing.','She likes reading, writing, and painting\" (all gerunds) not \"She likes reading, to write, and painting.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-39ffbf12-f995-4724-a660-76ce4bfecd4a','154',NULL),(24,'2025-06-14 16:01:50.832640',_binary '','2025-06-14 16:02:40.455638','Students will learn to identify the true subject and apply correct agreement rules in complex sentences.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-395908cc-f619-4150-bad4-c3edd106f80d','Subject-Verb Agreement',0,'Subject-verb agreement means that the verb must match the subject in number (singular or plural) and person (first, second, or third person).','\"The group of students is working on their project\" (singular subject \"group\" takes singular verb \"is\").','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/grammar/-1-3fe992e0-8525-4c19-aa0d-3663074bb009','155',NULL);
