INSERT INTO `grammar_tips` (`grammar_id`, `tip`) VALUES (2,'Use it for routines (e.g., I go to work at 8 AM).'),(2,'Use it for facts (e.g., Water boils at 100°C).'),(2,'Add -s/-es for he/she/it (e.g., He watches TV).'),(2,'Use do/does for questions and negatives (e.g., Do you like pizza?).'),(2,'Avoid using it for actions happening right now (use Present Continuous instead).'),(3,'Use \"am/is/are + verb-ing\" to form the tense.'),(3,'Often used with time expressions like \"now,\" \"at the moment,\" \"currently,\" \"today,\" or \"this week.\"'),(3,'Not used for permanent situations or general truths (e.g., \"I am loving pizza\" ❌ → \"I love pizza\" ✅).'),(3,'Can describe future plans when combined with a time reference (e.g., \"I am meeting her tomorrow.\").'),(3,'Common verbs like go, come, stay, work, study, play are often used in this tense.'),(4,'Use \"will\" for quick decisions, promises, or predictions.'),(4,'Use \"be going to\" for planned future actions.'),(4,'Often used with time expressions like \"tomorrow,\" \"next week,\" \"in 2025,\" or \"soon.\"'),(4,'Avoid using it for scheduled events (use Present Simple instead, e.g., \"The train leaves at 7 PM.\").'),(5,'Use for actions that happened at a definite time in the past (e.g., \"yesterday,\" \"last year,\" \"in 2010\").'),(5,'Regular verbs: add \"-ed\" (e.g., \"walk → walked\").'),(5,'Irregular verbs: memorize their past forms (e.g., \"go → went,\" \"eat → ate\").'),(5,'Questions and negatives use \"did\" + base verb (e.g., \"Did you go?\" / \"She didn\'t call.\").'),(6,'Use \"have/has + past participle (regular: -ed / irregular: 3rd column)'),(6,'Common time markers: ever, never, just, already, yet, since, for'),(6,'Don\'t use with specific past times (e.g., \"yesterday\")'),(6,'Shows present relevance of past actions'),(6,'Often contrasts with Simple Past (completed vs. connected to now)'),(1,'Add -s or -es to the verb when the subject is he, she, it (third person singular).'),(1,'Use \"do\" for I/you/we/they and \"does\" for he/she/it in questions and negatives.'),(1,'Do not add -s/es after the verb in questions and negatives.'),(1,'Common time expressions: always, usually, often, sometimes, never, every day, on Mondays, etc.'),(7,'Always use past perfect for the action that happened first, and simple past for the action that happened second. Think of it as \"the earlier past\" and \"the later past.\"'),(7,'Look for time expressions like \"before,\" \"after,\" \"when,\" \"by the time,\" \"already,\" and \"just\" - these often indicate when to use past perfect.'),(7,'For negatives, use \"had not\" or \"hadn\'t\" + past participle. For questions, put \"had\" before the subject: \"Had you finished your homework before dinner?\"'),(7,'Remember that past perfect always uses \"had\" + past participle. Regular verbs add \"-ed\" (worked → had worked), but irregular verbs have special forms (go → had gone, eat → had eaten).'),(7,'Only use past perfect when you need to show that one past action happened before another. If events happened in chronological order, simple past is often sufficient.'),(8,'Use with \"by,\" \"by the time,\" \"before,\" and specific future times.'),(8,'Always use \"will have + past participle\" (will have finished, will have traveled).'),(8,'Shows actions completed before a future point, not ongoing actions.'),(8,'Questions: \"Will you have...?\" Negatives: \"will not have\" or \"won\'t have\"'),(8,'Often used for goals, predictions, and milestones at future dates.'),(9,'Use with exact times like \"at 3 PM,\" \"tomorrow evening,\" \"next Monday.\"'),(9,'Always use \"will be + verb-ing\" (will be working, will be studying).'),(9,'Shows actions in progress, not completed actions or single events.'),(9,'Questions: \"Will you be...?\" Negatives: \"will not be\" or \"won\'t be + verb-ing\"'),(9,'Often used when one future action interrupts another ongoing action.'),(10,'Use for actions in progress at a specific past time or duration.'),(10,'Use \"was/were + verb-ing\" (was working, were studying, was sleeping).'),(10,'Often used with simple past to show interrupted actions: \"while,\" \"when.\"'),(10,'Questions: \"Was/Were you...?\" Negatives: \"wasn\'t/weren\'t + verb-ing\"'),(10,'Common with \"at 8 PM yesterday,\" \"while,\" \"when,\" \"all morning.\"'),(11,'Zero (facts), First (real future), Second (unreal present), Third (unreal past).'),(11,'Use comma after if clause when it comes first: \"If I study, I will pass.\"'),(11,'Never use \"will\" directly after \"if\" in the condition part.'),(11,'Choose the right conditional type based on reality and time.'),(11,'Zero: If + present, present. First: If + present, will + verb.'),(12,'Use \"be + past participle\" (is written, was built, will be completed).'),(12,'Use when the action is more important than the doer.'),(12,'Add \"by + agent\" only when the doer is important or unknown.'),(12,'\"Be\" changes according to tense, past participle stays the same.'),(12,'Only transitive verbs (with direct objects) can become passive.'),(13,'Who (people), which (things), that (people/things), whose (possession).\n'),(13,'Defining: essential info, no commas. Non-defining: extra info, use commas.'),(13,'Who/which can be subject or object in the relative clause.'),(13,'Don\'t use \"that\" in non-defining clauses or after prepositions.\n'),(13,'Can omit relative pronoun when it\'s the object of the clause.'),(14,'Zero Conditional uses present tense in both clauses for general truths and facts.'),(14,'First Conditional uses present tense in the if-clause and future tense in the main clause for real possibilities.'),(14,'Second Conditional uses past tense in the if-clause and \"would + base verb\" in the main clause for hypothetical situations.'),(14,'Don\'t use \"will\" in the if-clause when forming First Conditional sentences.'),(14,'Remember that the if-clause can come first or second in the sentence.'),(15,'Use passive voice when the action is more important than who performs it.'),(15,'Form passive with correct tense of \"be\" + past participle (be + V3).'),(15,'Add \"by + agent\" only when the doer is important or surprising information.'),(15,'Prefer passive voice in formal writing, scientific reports, and news articles.'),(15,'Remember that only transitive verbs (verbs that take objects) can be made passive.'),(16,'Move tenses one step back: present → past, past → past perfect, will → would.'),(16,'Change pronouns to match the speaker\'s perspective: I → he/she, you → I/they.'),(16,'Adjust time and place expressions: today → that day, here → there, now → then.'),(16,'Use \"told\" when mentioning the listener, \"said\" when not mentioning the listener.'),(16,'Add \"that\" after reporting verbs for clarity, though it\'s often optional in spoken English.'),(17,'Use \"a\" before consonant sounds and \"an\" before vowel sounds, not just consonant/vowel letters.'),(17,'Use \"the\" when both speaker and listener know which specific thing is being discussed.'),(17,'Use \"a/an\" when introducing something for the first time or talking about one of many.'),(17,'Don\'t use articles with plural nouns when speaking generally (Cars are expensive).'),(17,'Use \"the\" with superlatives, ordinal numbers, and unique things (the sun, the first, the best).'),(18,'Learn verb patterns: some verbs take only gerunds (enjoy, avoid, finish), others only infinitives (decide, plan, hope).'),(18,'Use gerunds after prepositions: \"interested in learning,\" \"good at speaking,\" \"afraid of flying.\"'),(18,'Some verbs change meaning: \"stop smoking\" (quit) vs \"stop to smoke\" (pause in order to smoke).'),(18,'Use gerunds as subjects of sentences: \"Swimming is good exercise\" sounds more natural than \"To swim is good exercise.\"'),(18,'Remember that gerunds can take objects and be modified by adverbs just like regular verbs.'),(19,'Use \"who\" for people, \"which\" for things, and \"that\" for both people and things in defining clauses.'),(19,'Use commas with non-defining clauses (extra information), but no commas with defining clauses (essential information).'),(19,'\"Whose\" shows possession and can be used for both people and things: \"the man whose car\" or \"the company whose profits.\"'),(19,'You can omit the relative pronoun when it\'s the object of the clause: \"The book (that) I read\" but not \"The book that won the prize.\"'),(19,'Use \"where\" for places, \"when\" for times, and \"why\" for reasons instead of preposition + which in informal speech.'),(20,'Add -er/-est to one-syllable adjectives (tall-taller-tallest), but use more/most with longer adjectives (beautiful-more beautiful-most beautiful).'),(20,'Remember irregular forms: good-better-best, bad-worse-worst, far-farther/further-farthest/furthest.'),(20,'Use \"as...as\" for equal comparisons and \"not as...as\" for unequal comparisons with the positive form.'),(20,'Double the final consonant for short adjectives ending in consonant-vowel-consonant: big-bigger-biggest.'),(20,'Use \"the\" before superlatives and often add \"in\" or \"of\" to specify the group being compared.'),(21,'Modal verbs never change form - no -s, -ed, or -ing endings (he can, not he cans).'),(21,'Always use base form of main verb after modals - \"can go\" not \"can to go\" or \"can going.\"'),(21,'Use \"can/could\" for ability, \"may/might\" for possibility, \"must/have to\" for strong obligation.'),(21,'\"Should\" gives advice, \"would\" is polite or hypothetical, \"shall\" is formal or offers help.'),(21,'Make negatives by adding \"not\" after the modal: cannot/can\'t, should not/shouldn\'t, must not/mustn\'t.'),(22,'Use base form of verb (without -s) after \"suggest,\" \"recommend,\" \"demand,\" \"require\": \"I suggest he go\" not \"he goes.\"'),(22,'Use \"were\" for all persons in hypothetical situations: \"If I were rich\" not \"If I was rich\" in formal English.'),(22,'After \"wish,\" use past tense for present unreality and past perfect for past unreality.'),(22,'Common subjunctive triggers include: suggest, recommend, demand, require, insist, propose, it\'s important that.'),(22,'In formal writing, avoid contractions and use full subjunctive forms for clarity and correctness.'),(23,'Keep the same grammatical form in lists: all nouns, all gerunds, all infinitives, or all clauses.'),(23,'Use parallel structure with coordinating conjunctions (and, but, or) and correlative conjunctions (both...and, either...or, not only...but also).'),(23,'Maintain parallelism in comparisons using \"than\" or \"as\": \"Running is better than walking\" (both gerunds).'),(23,'Check for parallelism in series of adjectives, adverbs, or prepositional phrases within the same sentence.'),(23,'Read sentences aloud - parallel structures create natural rhythm and flow that sounds balanced to the ear.'),(24,'Identify the true subject by ignoring prepositional phrases: \"The box of books IS heavy\" (subject is \"box,\" not \"books\").'),(24,'Collective nouns (team, family, group) are usually singular in American English: \"The team plays well.\"'),(24,'Indefinite pronouns like everyone, somebody, neither are singular: \"Everyone HAS finished the test.\"'),(24,'With compound subjects joined by \"and,\" use plural verbs: \"Tom and Jerry ARE friends.\"'),(24,'With \"either...or\" or \"neither...nor,\" the verb agrees with the nearest subject: \"Neither the teacher nor the students WERE ready.\"');
