INSERT INTO `listening` (`id`, `created_at`, `status`, `updated_at`, `description`, `image`, `title`, `views`, `audio`, `questions`, `transcript`, `route_node_id`, `preparation_id`) VALUES (1,'2025-05-17 10:15:13.966485',_binary '','2025-06-03 17:49:52.307956','This lesson helps students practice listening and understanding everyday conversations in a farm market context. Students will become familiar with words related to food, shopping and common communication expressions.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/1-96d97530-dbbb-4b72-8dc9-90492734fe7e','At the Farmers\' Market: Fresh Conversations',1,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-02b72ed8-d474-4f85-88a6-0d49ffd22551','14','Narrator: Listen to a conversation at a farmers\' market. \nVendor: Good morning! How can I help you today? \nEmma: Hi! I need some vegetables for dinner tonight. \nVendor: Everything here was harvested yesterday. What are you looking for? \nEmma: I\'ll need some bell peppers. How much are they? \nVendor: They\'re $1.50 each, or four for $5. We have red, yellow, and green. \nEmma: I\'ll take two red and one green. Do you have any broccoli? \nVendor: Yes, $2.75 per bunch. \nEmma: Perfect. I\'ll take one bunch. And these tomatoes look delicious! \nVendor: They\'re our specialty! $3.50 per pound. \nEmma: I\'ll take half a pound. And what would you recommend for a stir-fry? \nVendor: Try some bok choy. It adds nice crunch to stir-fries. \nEmma: Great idea! I\'ll take one. How much is my total? \nVendor: That comes to $10.50. \nEmma: Here\'s $11. Keep the change. \nVendor: Thank you! Would you like a bag? \nEmma: No thanks, I brought my own. When are you here each week? \nVendor: Every Saturday from 8 to 2, and Wednesdays from 3 to 7. \nEmma: Perfect! See you next week. \nNarrator: Now answer the questions about the conversation.',NULL,2),(2,'2025-06-01 20:30:28.901178',_binary '','2025-06-11 23:49:02.683317','This lesson focuses on improving listening skills through a conversation about maintaining cleanliness in public parks. Students will learn vocabulary and expressions related to hygiene and environmental responsibility.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/2-54d40167-f7d2-4b91-9510-e237a817bdfb','Keeping the Park Clean – A Listening Lesson on Public Hygiene',3,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-32ae01db-eb2b-434d-8ba2-409101bcff66','55,56,57,58,59','Emma: (holding a trash bag) Excuse me, could you please put your empty bottle in the recycling bin? It’s just over there.  \nJack: Oh, sorry! I didn’t see it. Thanks for reminding me. (picks up the bottle and walks to the bin)  \nLisa: It’s great that you’re volunteering to keep the park clean. More people should do this!  \nEmma: Absolutely! If everyone throws trash properly, the park stays beautiful. Did you know littering can harm wildlife too?  \nJack: Really? I never thought about that.  \nEmma: Yes! Plastic waste can hurt birds and small animals. That’s why we organize clean-up events every month.  \nLisa: That’s a wonderful idea. Maybe I’ll join next time!  \nEmma: That’d be fantastic! The more helpers, the cleaner our park will be.',NULL,5),(3,'2025-06-01 22:22:12.606944',_binary '','2025-06-03 17:51:14.618013','This lesson focuses on listening comprehension about preparing for a final math exam, with vocabulary and exercises to enhance understanding.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/3-fc867c1c-661d-4b1e-9086-af037ea00d23','Tomorrow’s Final Math Exam',2,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/3-8ac236f9-a8e4-4726-9b0d-9897e9f0a2dd','60,61,62,63,64','Narrator: Two students, Emma and Jake, are discussing their preparation for tomorrow’s final math exam. They share their study strategies and concerns.\nEmma: \"Jake, are you ready for the math exam tomorrow?\"\nJake: \"Not really. I still need to review the formulas. What about you?\"\nEmma: \"I’ve been practicing problems all week, but I’m still nervous.\"\nJake: \"Me too. I always get anxious before exams.\"\nEmma: \"We should focus on the hardest topics first.\"\nJake: \"Good idea. And we can use the calculator for the complex calculations.\"\nEmma: \"Let’s meet early tomorrow to go over everything one more time.\"\nJake: \"Perfect! I’ll bring my notes and extra pencils.\"',NULL,7),(4,'2025-06-02 13:46:17.646419',_binary '','2025-06-02 14:08:35.056485','This lesson focuses on listening comprehension about a new gaming console launch, with vocabulary and exercises to enhance understanding.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/4-1e87749a-c92a-4c0d-a346-877f08e473c9','New Generation Console Launch Event',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/4-ce7bb9c9-5207-4e4a-a982-8578315183d5','65,66,67,68,69','Presenter:\n*\"Ladies and gentlemen, welcome to the launch of our next-generation gaming console! This revolutionary system delivers unparalleled performance with true 8K resolution and 120Hz refresh rates. The redesigned controller features advanced haptic feedback for more immersive gameplay.\n\nOne of our key focuses was backward compatibility - your entire game library from previous generations will work seamlessly. The ultra-fast SSD storage eliminates loading screens, while our new cooling system ensures quiet operation even during intense sessions.\n\nWe\'re proud to announce 15 exclusive launch titles available on day one. Pre-orders start tomorrow at all major retailers. This isn\'t just an upgrade - it\'s a transformation in how you experience games!\"*',NULL,8),(5,'2025-06-11 18:57:26.310315',_binary '','2025-06-11 19:11:52.483636','This listening lesson focuses on understanding conversations about planning and organizing school events.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/5-e7bcb83c-0308-44d3-b325-76d61077df3c','Making It Happen: Organizing Successful School Events',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/5-f6be8fd2-cbb8-41ce-858a-8d0412d92fe0','131','Narrator Introduction: Today we\'ll listen to a planning meeting for Lincoln High School\'s upcoming Annual Cultural Festival. The conversation takes place between Mrs. Jennifer Park, the faculty advisor, and three student committee members: Marcus Williams, the event coordinator; Elena Vasquez, the budget manager; and David Kim, the logistics coordinator. They are meeting in the school conference room to finalize details for the festival happening in three weeks. This is their final major planning session before implementation begins. Listen carefully and answer the following questions.\nMrs. Park: Good afternoon, everyone. Thank you for staying after school for this important meeting. As you know, our Annual Cultural Festival is just three weeks away, and we need to finalize all the major details today. Marcus, could you start by updating us on the overall coordination status?\nMarcus: Absolutely, Mrs. Park. We\'ve confirmed participation from twelve different cultural clubs, including the International Students Association, the Drama Club, and the Music Department. Each group will have a thirty-minute performance slot and a display booth in the main hallway.\nElena: That\'s fantastic! From a budget perspective, we\'re in good shape. The school administration approved our request for two thousand dollars, and we\'ve received an additional eight hundred dollars in sponsorship from three local businesses: Miller\'s Bookstore, Sunrise Café, and Thompson\'s Electronics.\nDavid: Great news about the sponsorship, Elena! For logistics, I\'ve been working with the maintenance staff to set up the venue spaces. The main auditorium will host all performances, while the gymnasium will be converted into our international food court with tables and decorations representing different countries.\nMrs. Park: Excellent progress, everyone. Elena, could you break down how we\'re allocating our budget? I want to make sure we\'re spending wisely and not forgetting any important expenses.',NULL,29),(6,'2025-06-11 19:19:26.271265',_binary '','2025-06-11 19:36:34.984383','This listening lesson focuses on understanding conversations about dining at restaurants and food service interactions.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-a9adaad8-3a68-43d7-84ec-0c10998d6d73','Fine Dining Experience: Navigating Restaurant Services',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/6-7c802a17-ad51-4141-ae2f-fb5ff55d1143','132','Narrator Introduction: Today we\'ll listen to a conversation between Maria Santos, a restaurant manager at \"The Golden Fork,\" an upscale Italian restaurant downtown, and James Thompson, a regular customer who frequently brings business clients for dinner meetings. They are discussing the restaurant\'s new seasonal menu and special dining packages that cater to corporate customers. The conversation takes place in the restaurant\'s main dining area during a quiet afternoon before the evening rush. Listen carefully and answer the following questions.\nMaria: Good afternoon, Mr. Thompson! It\'s wonderful to see you again. I wanted to personally discuss our new autumn menu and some exciting dining packages we\'ve developed specifically for our business clientele like yourself.\nJames: Hello Maria, thank you for taking the time to meet with me. I\'m always interested in what\'s new at The Golden Fork, especially since I bring important clients here at least twice a month for dinner meetings.\nMaria: That\'s exactly why I thought you\'d appreciate hearing about our new \"Executive Dining Experience\" package. It includes a private dining room, a personalized menu consultation with our head chef, and dedicated waitstaff to ensure your business conversations flow smoothly without interruption.\nJames: That sounds perfect for the quarterly meetings I host with overseas partners. What\'s included in terms of pricing, and can you accommodate dietary restrictions? Some of my international clients have very specific food requirements.\nMaria: Absolutely! The package is priced at one hundred and fifty dollars per person, which includes a four-course meal, wine pairings, and all service charges. Our chef can accommodate any dietary needs - from vegetarian and vegan options to gluten-free preparations and religious dietary laws.\nJames: Excellent! I\'m particularly interested in the wine pairings since many of my clients are wine enthusiasts. Also, I\'d like to know about booking availability - I typically need to make reservations on short notice when clients are traveling through the city.',NULL,30),(7,'2025-06-11 20:03:54.985902',_binary '\0','2025-06-11 20:03:54.985902','This listening lesson focuses on understanding conversations about dealing with elevator breakdowns and using stairs as alternatives.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-2f29e494-f792-4171-8ccd-80d61a1e08b7','Managing When Elevators Are Out of Service',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-536495a7-c887-4837-a981-2535e0601977',NULL,'Narrator Introduction: Today we\'ll listen to a conversation between Dr. Sarah Mitchell, a physical therapist who works on the eighth floor of a medical building, and Tom Rodriguez, the building maintenance supervisor. They are discussing the impact of a major elevator breakdown that has been affecting the building for two days. The conversation takes place near the main stairwell entrance as Dr. Mitchell is preparing to climb to her office. She has mobility concerns due to a recent knee injury and is worried about repeatedly using the stairs. Listen carefully and answer the following questions.',NULL,NULL),(8,'2025-06-15 14:50:46.129579',_binary '','2025-06-15 14:53:17.019834','Students will listen to a conversation between friends discussing a cooking adventure where someone attempts to follow a traditional family recipe. ','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-b5957c8c-9933-4c78-874f-fa4832a0e0a8','The Great Kitchen Experiment: When He Followed Her Grandma\'s Recipe',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-1df9f661-2fa0-41ca-987f-f43bf581acd3','167','Narrator: Today we\'ll hear Sarah and Mike discussing Mike\'s recent cooking adventure. Sarah had shared her grandmother\'s famous apple pie recipe with Mike, and he decided to try making it for the first time. Let\'s listen to their conversation about how it went.\nSarah: So Mike, how did the apple pie turn out? I\'m dying to know!\nMike: Oh Sarah, it was quite the adventure! Your grandma\'s recipe looked so simple on paper, but I had no idea what I was getting myself into.\nSarah: laughing What happened? Don\'t tell me you burned it!\nMike: Well, not exactly burned, but... let\'s just say it didn\'t look anything like the picture you showed me. First, I couldn\'t figure out what \"a pinch of cinnamon\" meant. Is that like a teaspoon? A tablespoon?\nSarah: giggling Oh no! A pinch is just what you can hold between your thumb and finger!\nMike: Right, well I used about half a jar! Then when it said \"mix until smooth,\" I thought my arm was going to fall off. I must have stirred for twenty minutes straight.\nSarah: You didn\'t use the electric mixer?\nMike: What electric mixer? The recipe just said \"mix!\" Anyway, when I put it in the oven, everything seemed fine. But then this sweet, cinnamony smell started filling the entire apartment. My neighbors probably thought I opened a bakery!\nSarah: That actually sounds wonderful!\nMike: It was, until I realized I\'d forgotten to set a timer. When I finally remembered to check on it, the top was golden brown, but when I cut into it... let\'s just say the apples were still quite crunchy.\nSarah: laughing harder Oh Mike! You needed to bake it longer! But hey, at least you tried. How did it taste?\nMike: Surprisingly not terrible! The crust was actually pretty good, and despite the crunchy apples and excessive cinnamon, it had that homemade charm. I think your grandma would have been... amused.\nSarah: She definitely would have laughed and then showed you the right way to do it. Want to try again this weekend? I\'ll supervise this time!\nMike: Absolutely! But maybe we should start with something simpler... like toast?',NULL,53),(9,'2025-06-15 15:04:44.136447',_binary '','2025-06-15 15:07:19.304212','Students will listen to a cooking competition between two friends representing different culinary traditions - Japanese sushi-making and American burger grilling. ','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-47375468-b1ab-41fe-b0e1-863588e3eeea','Sushi vs Burger: Their First Cooking Battle',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-c0fa604f-25fa-4776-a987-cd4ca0594716','168','Narrator: Welcome to today\'s friendly cooking competition! We\'re in the kitchen with Yuki, a Japanese exchange student passionate about traditional sushi-making, and Jake, an American culinary student who believes the perfect burger is an art form. They\'ve decided to settle their good-natured debate about which cuisine requires more skill by having their first cooking battle. Let\'s listen as they prepare their signature dishes.\nJake: Alright Yuki, I hope you\'re ready for this! My grandmother\'s burger recipe has never been defeated.\nYuki: laughing Jake-san, we\'ll see about that! Sushi-making is a 200-year-old tradition. It requires patience, precision, and years of practice.\nJake: Years of practice? Come on! A good burger is all about timing, the right blend of spices, and knowing exactly when to flip. Plus, I\'m grilling these patties over real flames - that\'s where the magic happens!\nYuki: sounds of knife work Listen to this rhythm, Jake. chop, chop, chop Each cut must be exactly the same thickness. The fish must be fresh, the rice perfectly seasoned with just the right amount of vinegar and sugar.\nJake: sizzling sounds Okay, I\'ll admit that sounds pretty technical, but check this out - I\'m caramelizing these onions to perfection, melting aged cheddar, and my secret sauce has twelve different ingredients!\nYuki: Twelve ingredients? surprised That seems... excessive. In Japanese cooking, we believe in simplicity. The natural flavor of each ingredient should shine through. My sushi has only five components, but each one is perfectly balanced.\nJake: flipping burger Different philosophies, I guess! I\'m all about layering flavors - the smokiness from the grill, the richness of the cheese, the crunch of fresh lettuce, the tang of pickles...\nYuki: concentrating Now comes the most difficult part - shaping the nigiri. The rice must be warm, but not too warm. Too much pressure and it falls apart, too little and it won\'t hold together.\nJake: confident And here\'s my moment of truth - the flip! sizzling intensifies Perfect! Golden brown on both sides. The key is to never press down on the patty. That just squeezes out all the delicious juices.\nYuki: quietly focused The final touch - a tiny bit of wasabi between the fish and rice. Not too much, just enough to enhance the flavor without overpowering it.\nJake: assembling Bottom bun, special sauce, lettuce, tomato, onions, cheese, patty, more sauce, pickles, and... the crown! proudly Behold - the ultimate American burger!\nYuki: presenting carefully And here is my chef\'s selection - tuna, salmon, and yellowtail nigiri, prepared with respect for traditional techniques.\nJake: Wow, Yuki, that looks like art! So neat and colorful.\nYuki: Thank you, Jake-san. And your burger... it\'s so tall! How do you even eat something that big?\nJake: laughing Very carefully! Want to trade a piece? I\'m curious about that yellowtail.\nYuki: Of course! I\'d love to try your famous burger. Maybe we can learn from each other\'s techniques.\nJake: Deal! Though I still say burgers require more skill.\nYuki: giggling We\'ll agree to disagree, my friend!',NULL,54),(10,'2025-06-15 15:12:34.854934',_binary '','2025-06-15 15:14:07.564135','Students will listen to a humorous story about someone\'s first attempt at baking heart-shaped cookies for Valentine\'s Day that goes hilariously wrong.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-c25f54eb-977b-4788-87ca-c8b41c2b7326','The Mystery of the Burnt Cookies: A Valentine\'s Day Disaster',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-2f1dd5b2-373a-4f25-a484-3026a37be327','169','Narrator: Today we\'ll hear Emma telling her best friend Lisa about her Valentine\'s Day baking adventure. Emma decided to surprise her boyfriend David with homemade heart-shaped cookies, but as a complete beginner in the kitchen, things didn\'t go exactly as planned. Let\'s listen to her amusing tale of culinary chaos.\nLisa: So Emma, how did your surprise Valentine\'s cookies turn out? I\'m excited to hear!\nEmma: sighing dramatically Oh Lisa, it was a complete disaster! I should have just bought cookies from the store like a normal person.\nLisa: laughing Oh no! What happened? It couldn\'t have been that bad!\nEmma: Trust me, it was worse than you can imagine. So I found this \"foolproof\" recipe online that said \"Perfect for beginners - only 30 minutes!\" I thought, \"How hard could it be?\"\nLisa: Famous last words! giggling\nEmma: Exactly! First, I realized I didn\'t have a heart-shaped cookie cutter, so I tried to cut them by hand with a knife. They looked more like... well, let\'s say abstract art than hearts.\nLisa: trying not to laugh Okay, but they still would have tasted good, right?\nEmma: Here\'s where it gets interesting. The recipe called for \"two cups of flour,\" but I accidentally grabbed the bag of powdered sugar instead. I didn\'t realize my mistake until I was already mixing everything together.\nLisa: gasping No way! What did you do?\nEmma: I panicked! I thought maybe it would be okay - like, extra sweet cookies, right? So I just continued with the recipe. Then I couldn\'t find my measuring spoons, so I just... eyeballed everything else.\nLisa: incredulous You eyeballed the measurements?\nEmma: defensively I thought I was being creative! Anyway, when I put them in the oven, I set the timer for 15 minutes like the recipe said. But then I got distracted watching this romantic movie on TV, thinking about how surprised David would be.\nLisa: Please tell me you didn\'t forget about them...\nEmma: sheepishly Well, the smoke alarm reminded me! By the time I ran to the kitchen, there was smoke everywhere. I opened the oven and found these... charcoal sculptures that used to be cookies.\nLisa: bursting into laughter Oh my goodness! Were they completely black?\nEmma: Black as night! And the smell... Lisa, it took three days to get the burnt smell out of my apartment. My neighbors probably thought I was trying to burn the building down.\nLisa: still laughing What did you tell David?\nEmma: That\'s the best part! When he came over, he saw the kitchen still covered in flour, the burnt cookies on the counter, and me sitting there looking defeated. Instead of being disappointed, he started laughing so hard he couldn\'t breathe!\nLisa: Aww, that\'s actually really sweet!\nEmma: Right? Then he said, \"I love that you tried something completely out of your comfort zone for me. These are the most memorable Valentine\'s cookies I\'ve ever received!\" We ended up ordering pizza and laughing about it all night.\nLisa: That\'s such a perfect Valentine\'s Day story! Much better than regular cookies.\nEmma: smiling You know what? You\'re absolutely right. Next year though, I\'m definitely taking a baking class first!\nLisa: Or maybe just stick to your strengths - like ordering amazing takeout!\nEmma: laughing Hey! I\'ll have you know I make excellent restaurant reservations!',NULL,55),(11,'2025-06-15 15:16:45.905367',_binary '','2025-06-15 15:18:45.234667','Students will listen to a conversation between a couple attempting a yoga challenge together, where an experienced practitioner guides a complete beginner through various poses.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-59a04ea2-da5b-4a96-b168-420c2295a54d','Yoga Challenge: Can He Keep Up With Her Flexibility?',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-73de77ee-24d4-4c38-8daa-a823e55b610a','170','Narrator: Today we\'ll listen to Maya and Tom as they attempt a couples yoga challenge at home. Maya has been practicing yoga for three years and is quite flexible, while Tom is a complete beginner who spends most of his time at a desk job. Maya convinced Tom to try yoga together, promising it would be fun and relaxing. Let\'s see how their challenge goes.\nMaya: Okay Tom, are you ready for our yoga adventure? I promise I\'ll start with easy poses!\nTom: nervously Define \"easy,\" Maya. Remember, the most flexible thing about me is my work schedule!\nMaya: laughing Don\'t worry! We\'ll begin with a simple mountain pose. Just stand straight, feet together, arms at your sides. Feel your connection to the ground.\nTom: Alright, this isn\'t so bad. I can definitely handle standing up straight.\nMaya: Perfect! Now let\'s try a forward fold. Slowly bend forward from your hips, let your arms hang down naturally. Don\'t force it - just go as far as feels comfortable.\nTom: grunting slightly Comfortable? Maya, I can barely touch my knees! How are your hands flat on the floor?\nMaya: encouragingly That\'s totally normal for beginners! I couldn\'t touch my toes when I started either. The key is consistent practice and never pushing too hard.\nTom: straightening up Okay, what\'s next? Please tell me it gets easier.\nMaya: Let\'s try cat-cow pose on our hands and knees. Arch your back like a cat, then reverse it. It\'s great for spine flexibility.\nTom: getting down Like this? sounds of movement Wait, which way is cat and which way is cow?\nMaya: giggling You\'re doing cow when you should be doing cat! Imagine you\'re an angry cat - round your back up high!\nTom: adjusting Oh! Like this? I feel like I\'m playing charades with my spine!\nMaya: Exactly! You\'re getting it! Now let\'s try something a bit more challenging - downward facing dog.\nTom: cautiously That sounds... intimidating. Dogs are flexible, right?\nMaya: demonstrating From hands and knees, tuck your toes under and lift your hips up high. Make an upside-down V shape with your body.\nTom: struggling Maya... I think I\'m more of an upside-down W. My arms are shaking! How long do we hold this?\nMaya: supportively Just a few more seconds! Remember to breathe. Yoga is about finding your edge, not falling off it!\nTom: breathing heavily My edge was about three poses ago!\nMaya: laughing You\'re doing great! Let\'s try one more - warrior pose. Step your right foot forward, bend that knee, keep the back leg straight, and raise those arms up like a champion!\nTom: attempting I feel more like a wobbly flamingo than a warrior. How do you make this look so graceful?\nMaya: Years of practice and lots of falling over! You should see the videos of my first attempts.\nTom: finding balance Wait... I think I\'ve got it! I actually feel kind of strong in this pose!\nMaya: See? You\'re a natural! That\'s the warrior spirit coming through!\nTom: proudly You know what? This is actually fun. I feel taller somehow.\nMaya: That\'s the magic of yoga! It\'s not about being the most flexible person in the room. It\'s about being more flexible than you were yesterday.\nTom: Well, considering yesterday I could barely bend over to tie my shoes, I\'d say we\'re making progress!\nMaya: warmly I\'m proud of you for trying something completely new. Want to make this a weekly challenge?\nTom: enthusiastically Absolutely! But maybe next time we can start with those standing poses. I think I need to work up to the dog thing.\nMaya: Deal! And Tom? You did better than you think. Flexibility isn\'t just physical - it\'s mental too.',NULL,56),(12,'2025-06-15 15:45:59.921070',_binary '','2025-06-15 15:47:51.949352','Students will listen to two friends discussing their marathon training journey and race day experience, from being complete beginners to crossing the finish line.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-37a3ba02-a64e-48a3-957e-d49d5c77fb55','Their First Marathon: From Couch to Finish Line',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-d62f7c6e-a09f-4d15-b630-353cef0345f0','171','Narrator: Today we\'ll hear Alex and Jordan reflecting on their incredible marathon journey. Six months ago, these two best friends were typical couch potatoes who got winded walking up stairs. They made a crazy decision to sign up for their city\'s marathon, and today they\'re sharing their transformation story. Let\'s listen to how they went from sedentary to marathon finishers.\nJordan: Alex, I still can\'t believe we actually did it! My legs are killing me, but I\'ve never felt more accomplished in my life.\nAlex: exhausted but happy I know, right? Remember when we first signed up? You said we were completely insane, and honestly, you weren\'t wrong!\nJordan: laughing That first training run was brutal! We couldn\'t even make it around the block without stopping to catch our breath. I thought we\'d made a terrible mistake.\nAlex: Oh man, I remember that day! We were wheezing like old steam engines after just half a mile. My fitness tracker said I burned more calories walking to the fridge than during that \"run.\"\nJordan: chuckling But you know what? Week by week, something amazing started happening. Remember when we finally ran our first full mile without stopping?\nAlex: getting excited Yes! That was such a breakthrough moment! I felt like I could conquer the world. Then we set our sights on 5K, then 10K...\nJordan: The training schedule was intense though. Three runs a week, gradually increasing the distance. Some mornings I really didn\'t want to get out of bed, especially when it was raining.\nAlex: agreeing Those long runs on weekends were the real test. When we hit our first 15-mile training run, I thought my legs were going to fall off. But crossing that distance barrier was incredible.\nJordan: And the nutrition changes! Remember how we had to learn about carb-loading, hydration strategies, and energy gels? I never thought I\'d be someone who plans meals around running.\nAlex: groaning Don\'t remind me about those energy gels! They taste like flavored glue, but boy, do they work when you hit the wall at mile 20.\nJordan: Speaking of hitting the wall - race day was something else entirely. All those months of preparation, and then you\'re standing at the starting line with 30,000 other runners.\nAlex: getting emotional The energy was absolutely electric! All those people cheering, the music, the adrenaline... I got goosebumps just being there. But around mile 18, reality hit hard.\nJordan: sympathetically That\'s when the real mental game began. My body was screaming at me to stop, but somehow hearing our names being called by strangers kept me moving forward.\nAlex: The crowd support was unbelievable! Total strangers holding signs, offering high-fives, kids giving out candy. It was like the entire city was helping us reach that finish line.\nJordan: triumphantly And then we saw it - that beautiful finish line banner! I don\'t think I\'ve ever been so happy to see anything in my entire life.\nAlex: voice cracking with emotion When we crossed together after 4 hours and 47 minutes, I just broke down crying. All those early morning runs, the sore muscles, the doubts - it was all worth it in that moment.\nJordan: warmly The medal ceremony was perfect. Having that medal placed around my neck... I felt like an Olympic champion! It represents so much more than just running 26.2 miles.\nAlex: Absolutely! It\'s proof that we can achieve things we never thought possible. Six months ago, we were couch potatoes. Today, we\'re marathoners.\nJordan: looking ahead So... are you thinking what I\'m thinking about next year\'s marathon?\nAlex: grinning despite exhaustion Are you crazy? Ask me again when I can walk down stairs without grimacing!\nJordan: laughing Fair enough! But seriously, this experience has changed how I see challenges. If we can run a marathon, what else can we accomplish?\nAlex: reflectively You\'re right. This journey taught us that the impossible is just the untested. We proved to ourselves that with commitment and perseverance, we can transform our lives completely.',NULL,57),(13,'2025-06-15 15:59:44.413295',_binary '','2025-06-15 16:16:38.036526','Students will listen to a humorous conversation between two friends recounting a fishing trip where the inexperienced woman dramatically outperformed the self-proclaimed expert man.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-bce06a7d-1885-462b-b1ae-a912ee54546c','Fishing Fail: When She Outcaught Him 10 to 1',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-752cd34d-12cb-480a-a46b-2db76dfd2e77','172','Narrator: Today we\'ll hear Marcus telling his coworker Ben about last weekend\'s fishing expedition. Marcus, who considers himself quite the angler, took his friend Rachel on what he thought would be a relaxing day where he could show off his fishing expertise. However, things didn\'t go quite as planned. Let\'s listen to Marcus\'s somewhat embarrassing tale.\nBen: So Marcus, how was your big fishing trip with Rachel? I bet you impressed her with your legendary fishing skills!\nMarcus: sighing heavily Ben, I\'m never living this down. It was supposed to be my chance to show Rachel the ropes, you know? Teach her the fine art of fishing.\nBen: curious Uh oh, that doesn\'t sound good. What happened?\nMarcus: Well, I spent the entire boat ride explaining everything - the best baits, how to cast properly, where to find the fish, reading the water conditions. I was being the perfect fishing instructor.\nBen: encouragingly That sounds helpful! Rachel must have appreciated the guidance.\nMarcus: ruefully Oh, she listened politely to every word. I even demonstrated my signature casting technique that I\'ve been perfecting for fifteen years. She nodded and said \"That looks complicated.\"\nBen: sensing trouble Please tell me this story doesn\'t end with you catching nothing...\nMarcus: defensively Hey, I caught one fish! A perfectly respectable bass, about eight inches long. I was pretty proud of it, actually.\nBen: confused Wait, that doesn\'t sound like a disaster. One fish isn\'t bad for a day trip.\nMarcus: pause Ben... Rachel caught ten fish. Ten! And not little ones either - some of them were bigger than my prize bass!\nBen: laughing No way! How is that even possible?\nMarcus: frustrated I have no idea! She just sat there quietly, cast her line wherever she felt like it, and every ten minutes she was reeling something in. Meanwhile, I\'m checking my equipment, changing lures, moving to different spots...\nBen: amused What was her technique? Maybe she\'s a secret fishing prodigy!\nMarcus: That\'s the most infuriating part! There was no technique! She would cast randomly, sometimes getting her line tangled, and fish would just... appear on her hook like magic!\nBen: trying not to laugh Did she say anything while she was destroying your fishing reputation?\nMarcus: embarrassed She kept apologizing! Every time she caught another fish, she\'d say \"Oh, I\'m sorry! Is this beginner\'s luck?\" By the fifth fish, I was starting to question everything I know about angling.\nBen: grinning What about the other people on the lake? Did they notice?\nMarcus: groaning Oh, they noticed alright. Other fishermen started rowing over to ask Rachel for advice! Can you imagine? They completely ignored me - the guy with fifteen years of experience - and wanted tips from the woman who\'d been fishing for exactly three hours!\nBen: bursting with laughter That\'s absolutely priceless! What did Rachel tell them?\nMarcus: incredulous She said, and I quote, \"I just put the worm on the hook and drop it in the water. The fish seem to like it!\" The worst part? They all nodded like she\'d shared some ancient fishing wisdom!\nBen: wiping tears from laughing How did the day end?\nMarcus: resigned Well, when we got back to shore, Rachel insisted on taking a photo of our catches. There she is, grinning with her bucket full of fish, and there I am, holding up my one lonely bass like it\'s a trophy.\nBen: still chuckling Did you at least learn something from the experience?\nMarcus: thoughtfully You know what? I actually did. Sometimes it\'s better to be lucky than skilled. And Rachel taught me that overthinking can be the enemy of success.\nBen: teasingly So are you going to ask her for fishing lessons now?\nMarcus: laughing despite himself Very funny, Ben. But honestly? Next time we go fishing, I\'m just going to relax and enjoy the day instead of trying to be the expert all the time.\nBen: warmly That sounds like a much better approach. Plus, now you have a great story to tell!\nMarcus: grinning True! And Rachel\'s already planning our next fishing adventure. She promised to share her \"secret technique\" with me.',NULL,58),(14,'2025-06-15 16:24:07.651368',_binary '','2025-06-15 16:25:55.825022','Students will listen to two friends recounting their disastrous paint night experience where their attempt at following an instructor\'s landscape tutorial resulted in an unintentional abstract art creation.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-521eb2f8-7061-4517-84e1-2ccbd23b92ed','Paint Night Gone Wrong: Their Abstract Masterpiece',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-9d4e07f0-3bc0-4ea8-b0fd-8544495f017c','173','Narrator: Today we\'ll hear Sophie and Kevin discussing their recent paint night experience at a local art studio. What was supposed to be a relaxing evening following a simple landscape painting tutorial turned into a hilarious creative disaster. Sophie and Kevin, both complete art novices, discovered that sometimes the best masterpieces come from the most unexpected mistakes. Let\'s listen to their amusing recap.\nKevin: Sophie, I\'m still finding paint under my fingernails! Last night was absolutely chaotic, but I haven\'t laughed that hard in months.\nSophie: giggling I know! When we signed up for \"Peaceful Sunset Over Mountains,\" I never imagined we\'d end up creating... whatever that thing is hanging on my wall right now.\nKevin: chuckling The instructor, Janet, made it look so simple during the demonstration. \"Just blend the orange into the pink for a beautiful sunset gradient,\" she said. How hard could it be?\nSophie: sarcastically Right! Famous last words. The moment I tried to blend those colors, they turned into this muddy brown mess that looked more like a storm cloud than a sunset.\nKevin: laughing At least you stayed in the lines! I somehow managed to get paint everywhere except where it was supposed to go. My mountains looked like purple dinosaurs having a party.\nSophie: bursting into laughter Purple dinosaurs! That\'s exactly what they looked like! And remember when you accidentally knocked over your water jar?\nKevin: groaning How could I forget? The dirty paint water went flying across our canvases right when we were working on the foreground details. I thought we were doomed.\nSophie: amused But that\'s when things got interesting! The water created these amazing drip effects down our paintings. Janet even came over to see what we\'d done.\nKevin: proudly She said, \"Oh my! This is very... avant-garde. You\'re really thinking outside the box!\" I couldn\'t tell if she was being polite or genuinely impressed.\nSophie: enthusiastically I think she was impressed! Those water streaks turned our disaster into something that actually looked intentional. Like we were channeling Jackson Pollock or something.\nKevin: reflectively You know what the best part was? Everyone else in the class was so focused on making their paintings look exactly like the example. Ours was the only one that was completely unique.\nSophie: agreeing Exactly! Mrs. Henderson next to us kept erasing and repainting the same cloud over and over. She looked so stressed, while we were just having fun with our chaos.\nKevin: remembering And then you had that brilliant idea to add those wild brush strokes across the whole canvas when your brush started fraying.\nSophie: excited Those weren\'t intentional either! My brush was falling apart, and I thought, \"Well, if this painting is already ruined, might as well go crazy.\" So I just started making these big, sweeping gestures.\nKevin: admiringly The result was incredible though! All those layered textures and unexpected color combinations. It actually looked like a real piece of modern art.\nSophie: thoughtfully It made me realize that sometimes the best creativity comes from just letting go of expectations. We were so worried about following the rules that we almost missed the fun.\nKevin: enthusiastically And now we have this amazing story to tell! Plus, your painting genuinely looks like something you\'d see in a gallery. Very abstract expressionist.\nSophie: laughing I love how we\'ve gone from calling it a disaster to describing it as \"abstract expressionist.\" Art terminology makes everything sound more sophisticated!\nKevin: jokingly We should start our own art movement: \"Accidental Abstractism\" - where mistakes become masterpieces.\nSophie: playing along Perfect! Our motto can be \"Embrace the chaos, create the unexpected.\" I think we\'re onto something revolutionary here.\nKevin: warmly All joking aside, I\'m really glad we did this together. It was such a bonding experience, even if we failed spectacularly at landscape painting.\nSophie: affectionately Failed? Kevin, I think we succeeded at something much better - we discovered that art is about expression, not perfection. Plus, we have the most unique paintings in the entire class.\nKevin: grinning True! And I\'m definitely signing us up for the next paint night. Maybe \"Still Life with Fruit\" - what could possibly go wrong with that?\nSophie: laughing Famous last words again! But you know what? I\'m absolutely in. Our fruit might end up looking like abstract shapes, but it\'ll be our abstract shapes.',NULL,59),(15,'2025-06-15 16:40:45.620798',_binary '','2025-06-15 16:43:44.623079','Students will listen to two friends recounting their disastrous paint night experience where their attempt at following an instructor\'s landscape tutorial resulted in an unintentional abstract art creation. This lesson focuses on art vocabulary, describing mistakes humorously, and expressions for creative disasters.','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-28cd436c-278f-40b4-a38b-82509b0f9513','Paint Night Gone Wrong: Their Abstract Masterpiece',0,'http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/listening/-1-cef3fc60-f6c6-4f22-b207-610373499f67','174','Narrator: Today we\'ll hear Sophie and Kevin discussing their recent paint night experience at a local art studio. What was supposed to be a relaxing evening following a simple landscape painting tutorial turned into a hilarious creative disaster. Sophie and Kevin, both complete art novices, discovered that sometimes the best masterpieces come from the most unexpected mistakes. Let\'s listen to their amusing recap.\nKevin: Sophie, I\'m still finding paint under my fingernails! Last night was absolutely chaotic, but I haven\'t laughed that hard in months.\nSophie: giggling I know! When we signed up for \"Peaceful Sunset Over Mountains,\" I never imagined we\'d end up creating... whatever that thing is hanging on my wall right now.\nKevin: chuckling The instructor, Janet, made it look so simple during the demonstration. \"Just blend the orange into the pink for a beautiful sunset gradient,\" she said. How hard could it be?\nSophie: sarcastically Right! Famous last words. The moment I tried to blend those colors, they turned into this muddy brown mess that looked more like a storm cloud than a sunset.\nKevin: laughing At least you stayed in the lines! I somehow managed to get paint everywhere except where it was supposed to go. My mountains looked like purple dinosaurs having a party.\nSophie: burst