INSERT INTO `test_listening` (`id`, `created_at`, `status`, `updated_at`, `audio`, `questions`, `transcript`) VALUES (1,'2025-05-17 10:43:55.178490',_binary '','2025-05-17 10:45:46.155767','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-856089bb-8f41-4bf9-89e8-cb63a2c8ee80','7,8','Marine Biologist: Ocean acidification is often called climate change\'s \"evil twin.\" As the ocean absorbs carbon dioxide from the atmosphere, it forms carbonic acid, gradually lowering the ocean\'s pH.'),(2,'2025-05-17 11:13:13.734575',_binary '','2025-05-17 11:13:55.113253','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-dc1c6f81-bb34-493f-80a5-56578ee0cb97','180,181,182','Ocean acidification is often called climate change\'s \"evil twin.\" As the ocean absorbs carbon dioxide from the atmosphere, it forms carbonic acid, gradually lowering the ocean\'s pH. '),(4,'2025-05-31 16:02:10.391611',_binary '','2025-05-31 16:07:05.805998','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-b880cde2-bb9f-4603-b9aa-8e339f74db81','103,104,105','Garden Designer: Traditional Japanese gardens are carefully designed landscapes that embody key principles of Japanese aesthetics and philosophy. Unlike Western gardens that often showcase symmetry and colorful flowers, Japanese gardens aim to create miniature idealized landscapes using elements like rocks, water, moss, pruned trees, and carefully placed stone lanterns. These gardens emerged from native Shinto beliefs, later influenced by Chinese landscape painting and Zen Buddhism. Each element carries symbolic meaning – rocks might represent mountains or islands, raked gravel patterns suggest water ripples, and carefully pruned pine trees symbolize longevity and resilience. The three main styles are tsukiyama (hill gardens), karesansui (dry landscape gardens), and chaniwa (tea gardens). While tsukiyama gardens feature ponds, streams, and hills creating a miniaturized natural landscape, karesansui gardens like the famous Ryoan-ji in Kyoto use only rocks and raked gravel to suggest mountains and water, inviting viewers to meditate on nature\'s essence rather than its literal appearance.'),(5,'2025-05-31 16:02:44.081725',_binary '','2025-05-31 16:07:05.853377','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-e522e98c-fd75-48e0-80b2-eb584ef1de15','106,107,108','Historian: The Industrial Revolution, which began in Britain in the late 18th century and spread across Europe and North America in the 19th century, represents one of history\'s most transformative periods. Prior to industrialization, manufacturing was done by hand in homes or small workshops, but the development of machinery, new energy sources, and factory systems dramatically changed how goods were produced. The textile industry led the way with inventions like the spinning jenny and power loom, which mechanized the production of cloth. The steam engine, perfected by James Watt in the 1770s, provided reliable power that wasn\'t dependent on wind or water, allowing factories to be built anywhere. While industrialization created unprecedented economic growth and material prosperity, it also brought significant social challenges, including dangerous working conditions, child labor, urban overcrowding, and environmental pollution. Factory owners and investors accumulated enormous wealth, while many workers experienced poor living conditions and economic insecurity, leading to labor movements and eventually to reforms that improved working conditions and expanded political rights.'),(6,'2025-05-31 16:35:43.781924',_binary '','2025-05-31 16:40:53.350491','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-6f678d7c-ae72-4341-bdc0-abb369eaa89b','168,169,170','Immunologist: The immune system is your body\'s defense network against infectious organisms and other invaders. It\'s composed of various cells, tissues, and organs that work together to protect you from pathogens like bacteria, viruses, fungi, and parasites. The system has two main components: innate immunity and adaptive immunity. Innate immunity represents your first line of defense with physical barriers like skin and mucous membranes, along with general immune responses that activate quickly but don\'t target specific threats. Adaptive immunity develops throughout your life as you\'re exposed to diseases or vaccines, creating a \"memory\" that allows for stronger, targeted responses to specific pathogens upon re-exposure. Key players in this system include white blood cells called lymphocytes – particularly B cells, which produce antibodies that tag invaders for destruction, and T cells, which directly attack infected or abnormal cells. Dendritic cells act as messengers, capturing pathogen information and presenting it to other immune cells to coordinate an appropriate response. When functioning properly, this complex system maintains a delicate balance between defending against threats while avoiding harmful responses against the body\'s own tissues or beneficial organisms.'),(7,'2025-05-31 16:36:02.671974',_binary '','2025-05-31 16:40:53.390618','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-c1262744-801a-4f00-be8d-cac0653a0482','171,172,173','Financial Analyst: Financial markets serve as the backbone of modern economies, allowing companies to raise capital, investors to grow wealth, and governments to fund operations and projects. The stock market represents ownership in public companies, with stock prices theoretically reflecting a company\'s current value and future prospects. When you buy a share of stock, you\'re purchasing a small piece of that company. In contrast, bond markets represent debt – when you buy a bond, you\'re essentially lending money to the issuer, whether a corporation or government, who promises to pay you back with interest. Interest rates and bond prices have an inverse relationship – when interest rates rise, existing bond prices fall, and vice versa. Commodity markets trade raw materials like gold, oil, and agricultural products, while foreign exchange markets facilitate currency conversion and international trade. Market participants range from individual retail investors to massive institutional investors like pension funds and insurance companies. Understanding market psychology is crucial, as markets often react to perceptions and expectations as much as to fundamental economic data. This explains why markets can sometimes appear disconnected from economic realities as they price in anticipated future conditions rather than just current circumstances.'),(8,'2025-05-31 16:43:06.029061',_binary '','2025-05-31 16:48:41.486050','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-b1951343-68fd-4169-b4fb-c6746c50c02d','183,184,185','Archaeologist: Modern archaeology has evolved far beyond simply digging for artifacts. Before excavation begins, archaeologists use various non-invasive techniques to understand what might lie beneath the surface. Ground-penetrating radar sends radio waves into the soil and measures their reflection to create images of buried structures without disturbing them. Magnetometry detects subtle variations in the Earth\'s magnetic field caused by human activity, while electrical resistivity measures how easily electric current flows through the soil – features like stone walls or ditches have different resistivity than undisturbed earth. When excavation does occur, it\'s conducted methodically in a grid system, with each artifact\'s precise location recorded in three dimensions. Even seemingly insignificant items like plant remains, animal bones, and pollen are carefully collected, as they provide crucial information about ancient diets, environments, and climates. In the lab, techniques like radiocarbon dating can determine an organic object\'s age by measuring remaining amounts of the radioactive isotope carbon-14, while dendrochronology uses tree ring patterns to establish precise chronologies. Today\'s archaeologists also employ geographic information systems (GIS) to analyze spatial relationships between archaeological features across landscapes, helping reveal patterns of settlement, trade, and cultural change over time.'),(9,'2025-05-31 16:57:48.844907',_binary '','2025-05-31 17:06:22.742495','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-79faeec8-a626-495e-9824-d1d6e0ee8c2a','189,190,191','Meteorologist: Clouds form through a process that demonstrates basic principles of atmospheric physics. It begins with evaporation, as the sun\'s heat causes water from oceans, lakes, rivers, and even plants to transform into water vapor. This invisible gas rises into the atmosphere through convection, the same process that makes hot air balloons float. As water vapor ascends, it encounters cooler temperatures, since the atmosphere gets approximately 3.5°F cooler with every 1,000 feet of elevation. When the air reaches its dew point—the temperature at which it becomes saturated—condensation occurs. However, water vapor typically needs a surface to condense upon, which in the atmosphere comes in the form of tiny particles called condensation nuclei. These microscopic bits of dust, salt, smoke, or pollution serve as collection points where water droplets can form. When billions of these tiny droplets cluster together, they become visible as clouds. Different types of clouds form at different altitudes and under varying atmospheric conditions. Stratus clouds form in horizontal layers, often appearing as gray blankets covering the sky. Cumulus clouds are puffy with flat bottoms and rounded tops, developing vertically on warm days as heated air rises. Cirrus clouds, appearing wispy and thin, form at high altitudes where temperatures are so cold that they consist primarily of ice crystals rather than water droplets.'),(10,'2025-05-31 18:08:42.171282',_binary '','2025-05-31 18:13:50.549938','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-e373ffcf-14cb-400b-a7ae-5de1b6c58a33','223,224,225','This is a boarding announcement for Flight 287 to San Francisco. We are now boarding first class, business class, and passengers with small children. Due to weather conditions, there is a 30-minute delay. The current departure time is now 3:45 PM instead of 3:15 PM. Please have your boarding passes ready. Thank you for choosing United Airlines.'),(11,'2025-05-31 18:10:52.149097',_binary '','2025-05-31 18:13:50.585527','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-9ec6a79f-fe70-43a6-983f-e78d697f2585','226,227,228','Good morning, everyone. I\'m pleased to announce that our company exceeded sales targets by 15% this quarter. We\'re implementing a new CRM system next month with training from November 5th through 9th in Conference Room B. We\'re also expanding to Seattle, creating 25 new positions. Applications open December 1st. Our annual company picnic is October 28th at Riverside Park. Please RSVP to HR by October 20th.'),(12,'2025-05-31 18:11:38.722068',_binary '','2025-05-31 18:13:40.042473','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-80504990-a5fc-4f9d-8902-d49caf6af0cd','229,230,231','Transform your body in 30 days with FitFast! Our program combines high-intensity training with nutrition plans. Sarah from Texas lost 25 pounds in 6 weeks, while Mike gained 10 pounds of muscle. For a limited time, FitFast is just $79.99 – that\'s 60% off the regular $199.99 price. This offer expires Friday at midnight. Call 1-800-FITFAST or visit www.fitfast.com. 30-day money-back guarantee!'),(13,'2025-05-31 18:11:50.712825',_binary '','2025-05-31 18:13:40.072351','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-1c451e70-41d4-45e2-a350-ecb986890578','232,233,234','Welcome to the Metropolitan Museum\'s Egyptian wing, featuring 4,000 years of history. To your right is Perneb\'s tomb from 2440 BCE, originally in Saqqara, Egypt. The centerpiece is the Temple of Dendur, built around 15 BCE and given to the US in 1965. The Egyptian wing is open 10 AM to 5 PM, until 8 PM on Fridays. Audio guides cost $7 and are available in four languages.'),(14,'2025-06-03 22:14:21.153783',_binary '','2025-06-03 22:19:18.257790','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-ae9a9961-4866-4906-beee-09e71ce03f1e','250,251,252,253,254','Context: Two friends, Mike and Sarah, are discussing their weekend travel plans over coffee.\nMike: Hey Sarah, I\'ve been thinking about our weekend trip to the mountains. Have you decided what you want to do there?\nSarah: Well, I really want to go hiking on Saturday morning. The weather forecast says it will be sunny and perfect for outdoor activities. I\'ve already packed my hiking boots and water bottles.\nMike: That sounds great! I was hoping we could visit the local farmers\' market too. I heard they sell amazing fresh produce and handmade crafts. We could go there on Saturday afternoon after our hike.\nSarah: Perfect! I love farmers\' markets. What about Sunday? Should we check out that famous viewpoint everyone talks about? I\'ve seen beautiful photos of it on social media.\nMike: Absolutely! The viewpoint opens at 8 AM, so we should leave early. I suggest we have breakfast at the hotel first, then drive up there. The journey takes about thirty minutes according to the GPS.\nSarah: Good idea. I\'ll set an alarm for 6:30 AM. Oh, and don\'t forget to bring your camera. I\'m sure we\'ll want to take lots of pictures. Have you checked if we need to make reservations for restaurants?\nMike: Yes, I\'ve already booked a table at that Italian restaurant you mentioned for Saturday night. They said they have live music on weekends, which should be fun.\nSarah: Wonderful! This trip is going to be amazing. I can\'t wait to get away from the city and enjoy some fresh mountain air.'),(15,'2025-06-03 22:25:27.446397',_binary '','2025-06-03 22:31:27.372949','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-54e66921-cb06-477e-ad3d-36ef297624c1','255,256,257,258,259','Context: Marketing expert Dr. Jennifer Adams is giving a presentation to business professionals about modern digital marketing approaches.\nDr. Adams: Good morning, everyone. Thank you for joining today\'s presentation on digital marketing strategies for small businesses. My name is Dr. Jennifer Adams, and I have been working in digital marketing for over fifteen years.\nToday, I will discuss three key areas that every business owner should understand. First, we\'ll explore social media marketing and its impact on customer engagement. Second, I\'ll explain how search engine optimization can dramatically increase your online visibility. Finally, we\'ll examine email marketing campaigns and their impressive return on investment.\nLet me start with social media marketing. Recent studies show that 85% of consumers research products online before making purchases. Social media platforms like Facebook, Instagram, and LinkedIn have become essential tools for reaching potential customers. Successful businesses post regularly, respond to comments quickly, and create content that their audience finds valuable.\nThe key to effective social media marketing is consistency and authenticity. Companies that post sporadically or use overly promotional language often struggle to build meaningful relationships with customers. Instead, businesses should share behind-the-scenes content, customer testimonials, and educational information that helps solve their audience\'s problems.\nNow, let\'s talk about search engine optimization, or SEO. When people search for products or services online, they typically click on websites that appear on the first page of search results. SEO helps your website rank higher in these search results, which means more potential customers will find your business.\nThe most important SEO practices include creating high-quality content, using relevant keywords naturally, and ensuring your website loads quickly on both computers and mobile devices. Many business owners make the mistake of trying to manipulate search engines with outdated techniques, but modern SEO focuses on providing genuine value to users.\nFinally, email marketing remains one of the most cost-effective digital marketing strategies available today. For every dollar spent on email marketing, businesses typically see a return of $42. However, successful email campaigns require careful planning and personalization.'),(16,'2025-06-03 22:33:44.949771',_binary '','2025-06-03 23:17:41.520771','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/16-153d1817-8d57-40f6-a8d8-66b35dbf9120','260,261,262,263,264','Context: Environmental activist Maria Rodriguez is delivering a keynote speech at an international climate conference.\nMaria Rodriguez: Distinguished delegates, fellow environmentalists, and concerned citizens, thank you for being here today. I stand before you as someone who has witnessed firsthand the devastating effects of climate change in my home country of Costa Rica.\nOver the past decade, I have traveled to more than thirty countries, documenting environmental challenges and working with local communities to implement sustainable solutions. What I have learned is that environmental conservation is not just about protecting nature – it\'s about protecting our future, our children\'s future, and the future of every living creature on this planet.\nToday, I want to share three urgent messages with you. First, we must act now because climate change is accelerating faster than scientists originally predicted. Second, individual actions matter, but we also need systemic changes in how governments and corporations operate. Third, young people around the world are leading the fight for environmental justice, and we must support their efforts.\nLet me tell you about a village I visited last year in Bangladesh. Rising sea levels have forced entire families to abandon their ancestral homes. Children who once played in green fields now wade through salt water to reach their schools. This is not a future scenario – this is happening right now, today, as I speak to you.\nBut I have also seen incredible hope and innovation. In Kenya, I met farmers who have transformed degraded land into thriving agricultural communities using ancient techniques combined with modern technology. In Norway, I witnessed cities that run entirely on renewable energy. In Brazil, I worked with indigenous communities who have protected millions of acres of rainforest for generations.\nThese examples prove that solutions exist, but we need political will, financial investment, and global cooperation to implement them on a larger scale. We cannot wait for perfect conditions or complete scientific consensus. We must act with the knowledge we have right now.\nI challenge each of you to return to your countries with a commitment to make real, measurable changes. Whether you are a government official, a business leader, or an ordinary citizen, you have the power to make a difference. The question is not whether we can solve climate change – the question is whether we will choose to solve it before it\'s too late.'),(17,'2025-06-03 23:12:26.494090',_binary '','2025-06-03 23:17:20.100943','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/17-a6078d66-b6ee-43db-a338-7c61da1d0896','265,266,267,268,269','Context: Dr. Michael Chen, a computer science professor at Stanford University, is delivering a lecture about artificial intelligence developments to graduate students and industry professionals. Listen carefully and answer the following questions.\nDr. Chen: Good afternoon, everyone. Today I want to discuss the remarkable progress we have made in artificial intelligence and explore what the future might hold for this rapidly evolving field.\nArtificial intelligence has transformed from science fiction into everyday reality faster than most experts predicted. Just ten years ago, the idea of having intelligent assistants in our phones seemed impossible. Now, millions of people interact with AI systems daily, often without even realizing it.\nThe current generation of AI systems excels at specific tasks but lacks general intelligence. Machine learning algorithms can recognize images with superhuman accuracy, translate languages in real-time, and even generate creative content. However, these systems cannot transfer knowledge from one domain to another the way humans naturally do.\nI believe we are approaching a critical turning point in AI development. The next breakthrough will likely come from combining different types of artificial intelligence. Researchers are working on systems that integrate symbolic reasoning with neural networks, creating more flexible and adaptable AI.\nOne area where we will see significant progress is in healthcare. AI systems are already helping doctors diagnose diseases more accurately than traditional methods. In the next five years, I predict that AI will revolutionize personalized medicine, analyzing individual genetic profiles to recommend the most effective treatments.\nEducation is another field that will be transformed by AI. Intelligent tutoring systems will adapt to each student\'s learning style and pace, providing personalized instruction that was previously only available through expensive private tutoring. These systems will identify knowledge gaps and adjust their teaching methods accordingly.\nHowever, we must also consider the ethical implications of AI advancement. As these systems become more powerful, we need robust frameworks to ensure they are used responsibly. Questions about privacy, bias, and job displacement require careful consideration from both technologists and policymakers.\nThe key to successful AI development lies in interdisciplinary collaboration. Computer scientists must work closely with psychologists, philosophers, ethicists, and domain experts to create systems that truly benefit humanity.'),(18,'2025-06-03 23:19:25.866570',_binary '','2025-06-03 23:22:41.715867','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/18-1a7b6b02-eac7-499b-8a5a-89a9fc303b51','270,271,272,273,274','Context: CEO Rebecca Martinez is delivering the opening keynote at the Global Business Leadership Summit, addressing over 500 business executives about sustainable business practices. Listen carefully and answer the following questions.\nRebecca Martinez: Thank you for that warm welcome. It\'s an honor to speak to so many distinguished leaders who have gathered here from around the world to discuss the future of business.\nWhen I started my career twenty-five years ago, sustainability was considered a nice-to-have feature for companies, something that made good headlines but had little impact on the bottom line. Today, sustainable practices have become essential for long-term business success, and companies that ignore this reality do so at their own peril.\nThe statistics speak for themselves. Companies with strong environmental, social, and governance practices have outperformed their competitors by an average of 15% over the past decade. Consumers, especially younger generations, are increasingly choosing brands that align with their values. Investors are demanding transparency and accountability from the companies they fund.\nBut sustainable leadership goes beyond environmental concerns. It encompasses how we treat our employees, how we engage with local communities, and how we contribute to society as a whole. The most successful companies I have observed create value for all stakeholders, not just shareholders.\nLet me share an example from my own company. Five years ago, we implemented a comprehensive sustainability program that initially required significant investment. Many board members questioned whether we could afford these changes during a challenging economic period. Today, that program has saved us millions of dollars in operational costs while improving our brand reputation and employee satisfaction.\nThe transformation wasn\'t easy. We had to redesign our manufacturing processes, retrain our workforce, and rebuild relationships with suppliers who shared our commitment to sustainability. However, the results have exceeded our expectations in every measurable way.\nMoving forward, I believe businesses must embrace what I call \"regenerative leadership\" – the idea that companies should leave the world better than they found it. This means going beyond simply reducing harm to actively creating positive impact.\nThe companies that will thrive in the next decade are those that view sustainability not as a constraint, but as a source of innovation and competitive advantage. They will attract the best talent, earn customer loyalty, and build resilient business models that can withstand economic uncertainty.\nI challenge each of you to return to your organizations with a commitment to embedding sustainability into every aspect of your operations. The time for incremental change has passed – we need bold leadership and transformative action.'),(19,'2025-06-03 23:24:07.593485',_binary '','2025-06-03 23:27:12.848426','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/19-31d922b8-75df-4ce4-9752-b6be32ccb806','275,276,277,278,279','Context: Dr. Sarah Thompson, a climate scientist from the International Panel on Climate Change, is presenting her research findings on adaptation strategies at the World Climate Research Conference. Listen carefully and answer the following questions.\nDr. Thompson: Distinguished colleagues, thank you for joining this session on climate adaptation strategies. My name is Dr. Sarah Thompson, and I have been studying climate patterns and adaptation mechanisms for the past fifteen years.\nToday\'s presentation will focus on three critical adaptation strategies that communities worldwide have successfully implemented to address the impacts of climate change. These strategies have proven effective across different geographical regions and economic contexts.\nThe first strategy involves infrastructure resilience. Coastal cities around the world are implementing innovative flood management systems. The Netherlands has pioneered floating neighborhoods that rise and fall with water levels. Singapore has created an extensive network of underground reservoirs that collect rainwater during monsoons. Miami has invested billions in raising roads and installing advanced drainage systems.\nThese infrastructure projects require substantial initial investment, but they provide long-term protection against increasingly severe weather events. Economic analyses show that every dollar spent on climate adaptation saves between four and seven dollars in future damage costs.\nThe second adaptation strategy focuses on agricultural transformation. Farmers in drought-prone regions are adopting drought-resistant crop varieties that can survive with minimal water. In Bangladesh, farmers have learned to cultivate salt-tolerant rice in areas where rising sea levels have contaminated freshwater sources.\nTechnology plays a crucial role in these agricultural adaptations. Precision farming techniques use sensors and satellite data to optimize water usage and predict optimal planting times. These innovations have increased crop yields by up to 30% while reducing water consumption by 40%.\nThe third strategy involves ecosystem-based adaptation. Many communities are protecting and restoring natural systems that provide climate resilience. Mangrove forests act as natural barriers against storm surges and tsunamis. Wetlands filter pollutants and store floodwater during heavy rainfall. Urban forests reduce heat island effects and improve air quality.\nResearch has demonstrated that ecosystem-based solutions are often more cost-effective than artificial alternatives. A mangrove restoration project in Vietnam costs approximately $1,000 per hectare, while building artificial sea walls would cost $7,000 per hectare for equivalent protection.\nHowever, successful adaptation requires more than technical solutions. It demands strong governance, community engagement, and international cooperation. Countries must share knowledge, technology, and financial resources to ensure that all communities can adapt to climate change, regardless of their economic status.\nThe window for effective adaptation is narrowing rapidly. We have perhaps ten to fifteen years to implement large-scale adaptation measures before climate impacts become unmanageable in many regions. The science is clear, the solutions exist, and the benefits far outweigh the costs. What we need now is the political will and financial commitment to act decisively.'),(20,'2025-06-11 10:50:29.786531',_binary '','2025-06-11 11:10:04.098255','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-25dcf941-1bd2-4778-9315-896ec9aa5177','370,371,372,373,374','Good afternoon, everyone. I\'m Dr. Rebecca Thompson from the Environmental Science Department, and I\'m here to share some exciting news about our latest research project. Our groundbreaking study on ocean pollution has been completed after three years of intensive work. The research was conducted by a team of twelve scientists from five different universities across the country.\nThe project was funded by the National Science Foundation, and the results have been published in the International Journal of Marine Biology. Over 500 water samples were collected from various coastal areas during the study period. These samples were analyzed using advanced laboratory equipment that was specially designed for detecting microplastics.\nOur findings show that plastic pollution levels have been significantly underestimated in previous studies. The contamination was found to be 40% higher than what was reported five years ago. New filtering techniques were developed by our team to identify particles smaller than those detected in earlier research.\nThe data will be presented at next month\'s Global Environmental Summit in Geneva. We believe that urgent action must be taken by governments worldwide to address this growing crisis. Additional funding has been requested to expand our research to include Arctic waters, where similar contamination patterns are suspected to exist.'),(21,'2025-06-11 10:50:55.490261',_binary '','2025-06-11 11:10:04.137261','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-6acb21b1-1b22-4c58-8777-1449f6905d7f','375,376,377,378,379','Welcome to TechnoMax Electronics, one of the world\'s leading smartphone manufacturers. I\'m Sarah Martinez, your tour guide today. This facility was established in 2010, and since then, over two million devices have been produced here annually. The factory is operated by 1,500 skilled workers working in three shifts around the clock.\nLet me explain our production process. First, the circuit boards are assembled by automated machines in our clean room facility. The components are imported from certified suppliers in Asia and Europe. Each board is tested thoroughly before it moves to the next stage. Quality control checks are performed at every step of the process.\nThe smartphone cases are manufactured in our injection molding department. Recycled materials are used whenever possible to reduce environmental impact. The cases are then painted using eco-friendly coating techniques that were developed by our research team. After painting, the cases are dried in special ovens that maintain precise temperature control.\nFinal assembly is carried out by experienced technicians who have been trained for months. The devices are packaged using biodegradable materials, and each package is sealed automatically. Before shipping, random samples are selected and subjected to rigorous testing procedures. Our products are sold in over 80 countries worldwide, and customer satisfaction surveys are conducted regularly to maintain our high standards.'),(22,'2025-06-11 10:51:12.488773',_binary '','2025-06-11 11:10:04.172340','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-b06bfd2b-833f-4e3a-82cb-efd3affaa4f0','380,381,382,383,384','The construction of the Great Wall of China remains one of humanity\'s most remarkable achievements. This magnificent structure was built over many centuries by millions of workers, including soldiers, peasants, and prisoners. The earliest sections were constructed during the 7th century BC by various warring states. However, the wall as we know it today was largely completed during the Ming Dynasty between 1368 and 1644.\nThe project was initiated by Emperor Qin Shi Huang, who unified existing walls into one continuous barrier. Stone, brick, and earth were used as primary building materials, depending on the geographical location. In mountainous regions, stones were quarried locally and transported by hand to construction sites. The mortar that held the stones together was made from rice flour, which created an incredibly strong bond that has lasted for centuries.\nWatchtowers were positioned at strategic intervals along the wall\'s length. These towers were designed to house soldiers and store weapons and supplies. Signal fires were lit on these towers to communicate warnings about approaching enemies. The smoke signals could be seen from great distances and allowed information to be transmitted quickly across vast sections of the wall.\nSadly, much of the original wall has been damaged by natural erosion and human activities. Restoration efforts have been undertaken by the Chinese government since the 1950s. Today, the Great Wall is visited by millions of tourists annually and was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1987. Modern technology is now being used to monitor and preserve this ancient wonder for future generations.'),(23,'2025-06-11 10:53:46.056897',_binary '','2025-06-11 11:10:26.667239','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-eb14b81d-3960-4af1-9457-09fcb425a862','385,386,387,388,389','Good morning, Jennifer. Please have a seat. I wanted to discuss your interview yesterday with our department head, Mr. Williams. He said that you had made an excellent impression during your presentation. He mentioned that your technical skills were impressive and that you had answered all the questions confidently.\nMr. Williams told me that you had previous experience with similar projects, which is exactly what we\'re looking for. He also said that you seemed very enthusiastic about joining our team. However, he pointed out that you had admitted to having limited experience with our specific software platform.\nThe other interviewer, Ms. Davis from the IT department, reported that you had asked very thoughtful questions about the company culture. She said that you had inquired about professional development opportunities, which showed your commitment to growth. Ms. Davis also mentioned that you had explained your career goals clearly and that they aligned well with our company\'s direction.\nBoth interviewers agreed that you would be a valuable addition to our team. Mr. Williams suggested that we could provide additional training for the software you\'re not familiar with. He said that motivated employees like you usually learn new systems quickly. The team lead informed me that they would be happy to mentor you during your first few months.\nI\'m pleased to tell you that we would like to offer you the position. Mr. Williams asked me to tell you that the starting salary would be $65,000 per year, with a review after six months. He also wanted me to mention that you would have access to our comprehensive benefits package from day one.'),(24,'2025-06-11 10:54:00.461177',_binary '','2025-06-11 11:10:26.714049','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-4a4b3c08-7c10-4ee4-a054-dccd461ab876','390,391,392,393,394','Good evening, I\'m David Chen with Channel 7 News. Our top story tonight involves the city council meeting that took place this afternoon. Mayor Patricia Rodriguez announced that the city had approved funding for three new public parks. She stated that construction would begin next spring and that the projects would create approximately 200 new jobs.\nThe mayor explained that the funding had come from a combination of federal grants and local tax revenue. She emphasized that the parks would be designed to serve families from all income levels. Council member Michael Thompson said that he had been advocating for these parks for over two years. He told reporters that the community had been asking for more green spaces for families and children.\nIn other news, the police chief held a press conference regarding recent crime statistics. Chief Martinez reported that violent crime had decreased by 15% compared to last year. She said that the new community policing program had been very effective. The chief mentioned that officers had been working more closely with neighborhood groups and that this collaboration had improved trust between police and residents.\nWeather forecaster Lisa Park informed us that tomorrow would be partly cloudy with temperatures reaching 75 degrees. She predicted that rain was possible in the evening and advised that people should carry umbrellas if they planned to be out late. Ms. Park also warned that a cold front was approaching and that temperatures would drop significantly by the weekend.\nFinally, sports anchor Tom Wilson reported that the local baseball team had won their fifth consecutive game. He said that the team\'s performance had improved dramatically since hiring their new coach last month. Wilson added that ticket sales had increased by 30% and that the team was now in second place in their division.\n'),(25,'2025-06-11 11:01:11.469278',_binary '','2025-06-11 11:10:26.753646','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-8a938d2b-0fda-4705-becb-a67a2f6f2b00','395,396,397,398,399','Thank you for attending today\'s session on artificial intelligence in education. I\'m Professor Jane Mitchell from Stanford University. I\'d like to begin by sharing some insights from our recent survey of educators across the nation. Over 500 teachers responded to our questionnaire, and their feedback has been quite revealing.\nMany teachers told us that they were initially skeptical about using AI tools in their classrooms. However, those who had tried these technologies reported that students had shown increased engagement in their lessons. One high school teacher from Texas mentioned that her students had been asking more thoughtful questions since she started using AI-assisted learning platforms.\nSeveral educators indicated that they had concerns about academic integrity. A mathematics professor from UCLA said that he worried students might become too dependent on AI for problem-solving. He explained that he had been requiring students to show their work more explicitly to ensure they understood the underlying concepts.\nThe survey revealed interesting generational differences. Younger teachers stated that they felt more comfortable experimenting with new technologies. They said that they had been incorporating AI tools gradually into their curriculum design. In contrast, more experienced educators mentioned that they preferred traditional teaching methods and that they needed more training before they would feel confident using these new tools.\nLooking ahead, participants suggested that professional development programs should focus on practical applications. Many respondents said that they wanted hands-on workshops rather than theoretical presentations. One elementary school principal commented that her district had been planning to offer monthly training sessions and that teacher feedback would guide the program\'s development.'),(26,'2025-06-11 11:02:17.982860',_binary '','2025-06-11 11:09:48.333357','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-aa8ab411-b16c-4919-9f35-20802a823422','400,401,402,403,404','Welcome to our presentation about Edinburgh, Scotland, a city that offers visitors an incredible blend of history and modern culture. Edinburgh is the capital city of Scotland, which is located in the northern part of Great Britain. The city center, which was designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1995, attracts millions of tourists every year.\nThe most famous attraction is Edinburgh Castle, which sits majestically on top of an extinct volcano called Castle Rock. The castle houses the Crown Jewels of Scotland, which are among the oldest crown jewels in Europe. Visitors who are interested in history will also enjoy the Royal Mile, which is a historic street that connects the castle to the Palace of Holyroodhouse.\nThe Edinburgh Festival Fringe, which takes place every August, is the world\'s largest arts festival. During this time, performers whose talents range from comedy to dramatic theater come from around the world. The festival venues, which include everything from traditional theaters to temporary outdoor stages, showcase thousands of different shows.\nFor those who enjoy shopping, Princes Street is the main shopping area where you\'ll find both international brands and local Scottish products. The shops that sell traditional Scottish items, such as tartans and whisky, are particularly popular with tourists. There\'s also the Grassmarket area, which is known for its independent boutiques and vintage stores.\nFood enthusiasts will love the restaurants that serve traditional Scottish cuisine alongside international dishes. Many establishments that specialize in fresh seafood are located near the harbor area. The pubs whose atmosphere reflects centuries of Scottish tradition offer visitors a chance to experience local culture while enjoying a meal or drink.'),(27,'2025-06-11 11:02:35.079298',_binary '','2025-06-11 11:09:48.378973','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-97215626-f81e-4249-9ea8-5bd4f4960e89','405,406,407,408,409','Hello and welcome to Tech Today. I\'m Mark Stevens, and today we\'re reviewing the new smartphone that everyone\'s been talking about - the Galaxy Pro X15. This device, which was released just last month, has already generated significant buzz in the tech community.\nLet\'s start with the camera system, which is probably the phone\'s most impressive feature. The main camera, which has a 108-megapixel sensor, produces incredibly detailed photos even in low-light conditions. The night mode feature, which automatically activates in dark environments, has been improved significantly compared to previous models.\nThe phone\'s processor, which is based on the latest 5-nanometer technology, delivers exceptional performance for both daily tasks and intensive gaming. Apps that require significant processing power, such as video editing software and advanced games, run smoothly without any lag. The battery life, which lasts up to 18 hours with normal use, is another standout feature.\nThe display, which measures 6.8 inches diagonally, offers vibrant colors and sharp details. Users who enjoy watching videos or playing games will appreciate the 120Hz refresh rate, which makes everything appear incredibly smooth. The screen, which is protected by the latest Gorilla Glass technology, is also highly resistant to scratches and cracks.\nHowever, there are some areas where the phone could be improved. The price, which starts at $1,200, may be too high for many consumers. Additionally, the phone\'s size, which some users might find too large, could be a drawback for those who prefer more compact devices. The charging cable that comes in the box is also shorter than what many users would prefer.'),(28,'2025-06-11 11:02:51.620650',_binary '','2025-06-11 11:09:48.413908','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-5ad81e33-ed1a-454b-b0fe-714037dddf5e','410,411,412,413,414','Good evening, listeners. I\'m Sarah Williams reporting live from the Downtown Arts Festival, where thousands of art enthusiasts have gathered to celebrate creativity in all its forms. This annual event, which has been running for over fifteen years, showcases local and international artists whose work spans various mediums and styles.\nThe main exhibition hall, which houses over 200 different art pieces, has been completely transformed for this year\'s festival. Visitors who enter the hall are immediately greeted by a stunning sculpture installation that was created by Maria Santos, an artist whose work explores themes of environmental conservation. The piece, which is made entirely from recycled materials, sends a powerful message about sustainability.\nIn the photography section, we have work from photographers whose images capture the beauty of urban landscapes around the world. One particularly striking collection comes from James Chen, whose photographs of abandoned buildings have been featured in National Geographic. The black and white images, which were taken in Detroit and other former industrial cities, tell stories of urban decay and renewal.\nThe performance area, where live music and dance shows take place throughout the evening, has been bustling with activity. The stage, which was specially constructed for this festival, has hosted musicians whose genres range from classical to contemporary electronic music. Right now, we\'re listening to the City Orchestra, whose members include both professional musicians and talented students from the local music academy.\nFor families who are attending with children, there\'s a special interactive zone where young visitors can create their own artwork. The workshops, which are led by experienced art teachers, give children the opportunity to experiment with different artistic techniques. Many parents whose children participated last year have returned because their kids had such a positive experience.'),(29,'2025-06-11 12:31:48.209578',_binary '','2025-06-11 12:51:53.043622','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-0620ed0d-5daf-45dd-8118-613f2a4bbd58','462,463,464,465,466','\nAnna: Hi Mike! How are you doing?\nMike: Hi Anna! I\'m fine, thanks. What are your plans for this weekend?\nAnna: Well, on Saturday morning I\'m going to visit my grandmother. She lives about an hour away from here.\nMike: That sounds nice. What about Saturday afternoon?\nAnna: I\'m planning to go to the new shopping center with my sister. We want to buy some clothes for summer. Would you like to come with us?\nMike: Thanks for asking, but I can\'t. I have a soccer game at 2:00 PM on Saturday.\nAnna: Oh, that\'s exciting! Is it an important game?\nMike: Yes, it\'s the final match of our school tournament. I\'m a bit nervous but also excited.\nAnna: I\'m sure you\'ll do great! What about Sunday?\nMike: On Sunday, my family is having a barbecue party in our backyard. My cousins from another city are visiting us. You\'re welcome to join us if you want.\nAnna: That sounds wonderful! What time should I come?\nMike: Around 1:00 PM would be perfect. We\'ll have lots of food and music.\nAnna: Great! I\'ll bring some homemade cookies. See you on Sunday!\nMike: Awesome! Thanks, Anna. Have a good week!'),(30,'2025-06-11 12:32:08.286848',_binary '','2025-06-11 12:51:53.079654','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-674121f8-3111-4210-97a3-ffb530986fb8','467,468,469,470,471','Teacher: Good morning, everyone. Today, David will present his research about protecting our environment.\nDavid: Thank you, Ms. Roberts. Hello, classmates. Today I want to share some simple ways we can help protect our planet. Environmental protection is very important for our future.\nDavid: First, we should reduce the amount of plastic we use. Plastic bags and bottles take hundreds of years to disappear from nature. Instead, we can use reusable bags when we go shopping and drink from metal or glass bottles.\nDavid: Second, we need to save water. Many people around the world don\'t have clean water to drink. We can help by taking shorter showers, turning off the tap when we brush our teeth, and fixing any leaks in our homes quickly.\nDavid: Third, we should recycle paper, glass, and metal whenever possible. Recycling helps reduce waste and saves natural resources. At our school, we have special bins for different types of recycling materials.\nDavid: Fourth, planting trees is excellent for the environment. Trees clean the air and provide homes for many animals. Last month, my family planted five new trees in our neighborhood park.\nDavid: Finally, we can walk, ride bicycles, or use public transportation instead of always using cars. This reduces air pollution and helps keep our cities cleaner.\nDavid: In conclusion, if everyone makes small changes, we can make a big difference for our planet. Thank you for listening.\nTeacher: Excellent presentation, David! Does anyone have questions about environmental protection?'),(31,'2025-06-11 12:32:44.908048',_binary '','2025-06-11 12:51:18.652598','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-07c8c4ae-0b9d-49dc-ac9b-d76de0ef7173','472,473,474,475,476','Shop Assistant: Good afternoon! Can I help you find something today?\nCustomer: Hi! Yes, I\'m looking for a new shirt for work. Something formal but comfortable.\nShop Assistant: Of course! What size do you wear?\nCustomer: I usually wear medium, but sometimes large depending on the brand.\nShop Assistant: Here are some nice options. This white shirt is very popular, and we also have blue and gray ones.\nCustomer: I like the blue one. Can I try it on?\nShop Assistant: Absolutely! The fitting room is over there. Take your time.\nCustomer: Thank you. (After a few minutes) This fits perfectly! How much does it cost?\nShop Assistant: That shirt is $45, but we have a 20% discount today, so it\'s $36.\nCustomer: That\'s a great price! Do you accept credit cards?\nShop Assistant: Yes, we accept all major credit cards and cash too.\nCustomer: Perfect! I\'ll take it. Do you have a matching tie?\nShop Assistant: Yes, we have several ties that would look great with that shirt. This dark blue tie is very nice.\nCustomer: I\'ll take the tie too. How much for both items?\nShop Assistant: The tie is $15, so your total is $51. Would you like a shopping bag?\nCustomer: Yes, please. Thank you for your help!'),(32,'2025-06-11 12:33:51.697993',_binary '','2025-06-11 12:51:18.688074','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-83eb8202-53e8-4c82-81d0-11ef896f3624','477,478,479,480,481','Teacher: Good morning, class. Today, Alex will share with us about different hobbies and their benefits.\nAlex: Thank you, Mr. Wilson. Hello, everyone. Today I want to talk about popular hobbies and why they are good for us. Hobbies help us relax and learn new skills.\nAlex: First, let me talk about reading. Reading books is one of my favorite hobbies. It helps improve our vocabulary and imagination. I read for at least 30 minutes every day before bed. My favorite books are adventure stories and science fiction.\nAlex: Second, playing sports is great for our health. Many students in our school enjoy football, basketball, and swimming. Sports help us stay fit and make new friends. I play tennis twice a week with my brother.\nAlex: Third, creative hobbies like drawing, painting, and music are wonderful. They help us express our feelings and ideas. My sister loves painting landscapes, and she has won three art competitions this year.\nAlex: Fourth, cooking is a very useful hobby. When we learn to cook, we can make healthy meals for ourselves and our families. Last weekend, I made pasta with vegetables for my family, and everyone loved it.\nAlex: Finally, gardening teaches us about nature and patience. My grandmother grows beautiful roses and tomatoes in her garden. She says gardening makes her feel peaceful and happy.\nAlex: In conclusion, hobbies make our lives more interesting and help us develop new talents. I encourage everyone to try a new hobby this semester. Thank you for listening.\nTeacher: Excellent presentation, Alex! I\'m sure your classmates learned a lot about hobbies today.'),(34,'2025-06-08 03:29:38.482546',_binary '','2025-06-08 11:51:45.716026','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-22348a7e-1d07-4f01-9646-e70496cb4b0a','576,577,578','Available for students to follow along with the audio.'),(35,'2025-06-08 03:45:09.577917',_binary '','2025-06-08 11:51:45.783937','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-43ceffe7-f542-4081-a4c5-1308895d9bdb','579,580,581','Available for students to follow along with the audio.'),(36,'2025-06-08 03:49:01.044142',_binary '','2025-06-08 11:51:45.850694','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-022be16b-c4b9-435c-9280-f79725976ffe','582,583,584','Available for students to follow along with the audio.'),(37,'2025-06-08 04:53:08.901402',_binary '','2025-06-08 11:50:39.770869','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-9c5e8f46-3b75-4d5f-b36d-631937d919cd','616,617,618','Add a transcript for this listening passage (optional). This helps students follow along with the audio.'),(38,'2025-06-08 05:01:22.413141',_binary '','2025-06-08 11:50:39.833023','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-a2d5f624-f3be-4aab-97ef-dfc83fde14fc','619,620,621','Add a transcript for 