83,684','Welcome to our family dinner podcast. I\'m Sarah, and tonight we\'re discussing how families can improve communication during meal times. Our guest is Dr. Michael Chen, a family therapist with fifteen years of experience. Dr. Chen, many families today struggle with meaningful conversation during dinner. What advice do you have? Well, Sarah, the key is creating a safe space where everyone feels heard. Parents should start by asking open-ended questions like \'What was the best part of your day?\' rather than closed questions like \'How was school?\' which typically get one-word answers. It\'s also important to establish rules. No phones at the table is obvious, but families should also agree that dinner is not the time for criticism or discussing problems. Instead, focus on positive sharing and genuine interest in each other\'s experiences. One technique I recommend is the \'rose and thorn\' approach. Each family member shares one good thing that happened today and one challenge they faced. This creates balance and shows that it\'s okay to discuss both positive and negative experiences. Finally, parents need to model good listening. Put down your fork, make eye contact, and respond thoughtfully to what your children share. When children see that their parents truly value their thoughts and feelings, they become more willing to open up.'),(44,'2025-06-08 14:40:05.138026',_binary '','2025-06-08 14:42:06.947974','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-51e4c27a-437d-4e86-bea6-db54f2de3036','685,686,687','Hello, I\'m interviewing Mrs. Eleanor Thompson, age 78, about her relationship with her grandchildren. Mrs. Thompson, you have six grandchildren. How do you maintain close relationships with them despite the generation gap? Oh, it\'s wonderful that you ask! The secret is showing genuine interest in their world. I may not understand all their technology and music, but I ask questions and listen carefully to their answers. My grandson taught me how to use social media so we could share photos and messages. I also make sure to create special traditions with each grandchild. Every summer, I take each one individually on a day trip to somewhere they choose. Last year, my granddaughter wanted to visit an art museum, while my grandson preferred the science center. These one-on-one experiences are precious. Another important thing is respecting their parents\' rules while still being the fun grandmother. I never contradict their parents\' decisions in front of the children, but I do allow small treats and fun activities that make our time together special. The most important lesson I\'ve learned is that being a grandparent is different from being a parent. My job now is to love them unconditionally, share wisdom when asked, and create happy memories. I let their parents handle the discipline and serious conversations. Technology has actually helped us stay closer. We video call every Sunday, and my grandchildren send me pictures of their school projects and achievements. Even though we live in different cities, I feel very connected to their daily lives.'),(45,'2025-06-08 15:00:27.699765',_binary '','2025-06-08 15:06:33.050358','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-f7865ec0-cbd2-43ee-80ef-8ac8d74605aa','712,713,714','This transcript helps students follow along with the audio commentary and understand the specific terminology used in swimming competitions.'),(46,'2025-06-08 15:04:45.709877',_binary '','2025-06-08 15:06:33.104245','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test-listenings-temp-e186ea2b-961e-4439-b062-a037c0df2844','715,716,717','This transcript helps students understand the technical vocabulary related to sports psychology and mental training techniques used by professional athletes.'),(47,'2025-06-08 15:27:49.087862',_binary '','2025-06-08 15:37:10.340901','http://138.2.91.94:9000/h2t-english/test/listening/audio/test